# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-imperial
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The **1931 24 Hours of Le Mans** was the 9th Grand Prix of Endurance that took place at the Circuit de la Sarthe on 13 and 14 June 1931.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] With the demise of Bentley, the favourite for an outright victory was split between the Bugatti and Alfa Romeo works teams, with a lone privateer Mercedes as an outside chance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Once again it was one of the smaller fields, with only 26 starters.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] At the start of the race it was the Mercedes setting the pace from the Bugattis of Chiron and Divo.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] But tyre-wear was a big issue, with many cars suffering tyre blowouts and punctures.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This left Marinoni leading in the works Alfa.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Coming up to the first refuelling stops, the rear tyre on Maurice Rost's Bugatti blew out at full speed on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Rost lost control of the car and went through a fence, hitting three spectators, killing one.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] When more tyre issues plagued Chiron's car, the Bugatti team withdrew their remaining two cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Tyre troubles had also cost the Mercedes team eight laps.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Alfa Romeo of British privateers Howe and Birkin had been having a reliable race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] As others were delayed they caught them up and took the lead after midnight.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] At 2.30am a sudden thunderstorm swept the track.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Zehender went off at Indianapolis doing damage that eventually forced the works Alfa's retirement in the morning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Talbots of the British Fox & Nicholl team were running third and fourth with the Mercedes closing in again.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ivanowski was able to source some Dunlop tyres.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] He and Stoffel were able to pick up their pace, and when the leading Talbot was waylaid in the morning by chassis damage, the Mercedes was up to second by noon.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] At the finish, Howe and Birkin won by seven laps from the Mercedes and the remaining Talbot.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This was the first win at Le Mans for an Italian car, and in a record-breaking run, they claimed all three trophies – including the Index and Biennial Cup – and broke the 3000km distance for the first time.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Only six cars were classified, which has been the lowest ever number of finishers in the 24-Hour race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year there were no changes to the racing regulations of either the AIACR (forerunner of the FIA) Appendix C rules, nor those of the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO).
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The biggest change this year was in the pits.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Rather than refuelling with 10-litre cans, a series of 4-metre high reservoir towers were built holding 1000-litres.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Three hoses from each allowed gravity-replenishment at about 250 litres per minute.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Shell once again had the fuel contract and again offered its three standard fuel options.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The ACO also now allowed a mechanic to assist the driver with the refuelling.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] As usual, as engine power advanced, the ACO once again adjusted the Index target distances.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] With Bentley in major financial strife, the works team had been disbanded and the Bentley Boys dispersed, marking the end of an era.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Into this void came works teams from the two main powerhouses of current Grand Prix racing: Alfa Romeo and Bugatti.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] However, apart from Aston Martin, and a (non-eventuating) effort from Ariès the remaining entries were from privateer teams and "gentleman-drivers".
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were still only 30 cars entered, not a great improvement on the record low number from the previous year.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Of those, only four were entered in the final of the Biennial Cup – an Alfa Romeo, the two Talbots and the returning women in their Bugatti.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Daimler-Benz had pulled out of racing officially in 1930 leaving privateers to run their cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the 1930 race, the Mercedes of Rudolf Caracciola had taken the challenge to Bentley in the first half of the race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year, Paris-based Russian Valériani-Vladimir Tatarinoff, entered an SSK (*Super Sports Kurz*) on behalf of fellow émigré *Count* Boris Ivanowski.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] He had previously been denied an entry of a stripped-down Alfa Romeo for the 1928 race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The SSK had a big 7.1-litre engine that could be augmented temporarily by a Roots supercharger up to 250 bhp.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Along with his co-driver, Le Mans veteran Henri Stoffel, Ivanowski entered the car in both touring and Grand Prix races.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Bugatti had run almost exclusively in Grand Prix racing with great success in the late 1920s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year marked its first foray to Le Mans with a works team.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The new Type 50 was a development of the big-engined Type 46.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Its 5.0-litre straight-8 engine had a Roots supercharger and was capable of 250 bhp, and with a 3-speed gearbox, gave the car a top speed of 195 kp/h (120 mph).
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The team, managed by Bugatti's 22-year old son Jean, brought three short-wheelbase versions for their works drivers Louis Chiron / Achille Varzi and Albert Divo/Guy Bouriat, joined by Maurice Rost/Caberto Conelli.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Perhaps anticipating bad weather, they were running on a new, heavy-tread Michelin tyre.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Other innovations were a new quick-change brake system, "pop-top" petrol caps, and oil-refill tubes in the bonnet all designed to speed up pitwork.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Alfa Romeo had achieved great success in recent years with the 6C model, in both its regular or supercharged format.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Vittorio Jano's new design, the 8C, had a supercharged 2.3-litre engine that developed 155 bhp.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] It came in two styles: a short-wheelbase, 2-seater *corto* adapted for Grand Prix racing and narrow, tight circuits like the Mille Miglia; and a 4-seater *lungo* (long) version for the ACO regulations for touring cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although the Scuderia Ferrari ran the car for Italian races, it was a works team that arrived at Le Mans with two cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The driver-pairings were team regulars Giuseppe Campari / Attilio Marinoni and "Nando" Minoia / "Freddy" Zehender.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Two Englishmen were some of the early purchasers of the new model.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] *Sir* Henry "Tim" Birkin had given up his Blower Bentley project for the more reliable Alfa, and won his class first time up at the Irish Grand Prix the week before Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] *Earl* Francis Howe had his delivered to replace his 6C that Achille Varzi had crashed in the 1930 Irish race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] So in the 1930 Le Mans, Howe had run his Mercedes-Benz instead, earning one of the four entries taken up for the Biennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] For this race, he approached Birkin to be his co-driver The Bentley 4½ Litre that Birkin had raced in 1928 (and then Earl Howe in 1929) had been purchased Anthony Bevan who bought it back for a third run at Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Since the previous race, the great brand had been sold to Rolls-Royce.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Unlike most other car companies, Talbot had been reasonably successful with sales of its 6-cylinder car range.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Its latest version, the 105, now had a 3-litre capable of 120 bhp and 175 kp/h (110 mph), as well as a 4-speed gearbox and a bigger 160-litre fuel-tank.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Four cars were made available to the Fox & Nicholl team.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Two were taken to Le Mans to race with another as a test vehicle.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The drivers were team-regulars Brian Lewis, *Baron* Essendon / Johnny Hindmarsh and Tim Rose-Richards / Owen Saunders-Davies.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Henri de Costier had driven at Le Mans three times in the late-'20s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year he organised the entry of a pair of big Chrysler straight-8s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] He, himself, drove the larger 6.3-litre, 125 bhp, CG Imperial Eight while the new model CD Eight (with a 100 bhp 3.9-litre engine) was entrusted to the new, young French talent, Raymond Sommer.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] La Lorraine-Dietrich had not competed at Le Mans since 1926, after the company believed they were denied victory in the Biennial Cup by the ACO on a technicality.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The team's four B3-6 Le Mans specials had been mothballed until one was sold to Henri Trébor, who got the car a few days before the race after a factory refit.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Racing journalist Roger Labric submitted an entry on his behalf.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Trébor engaged Louis Balart as his co-driver, himself a veteran of the first four Le Mans races.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The small Scottish car company of Arrol-Aster arrived for its only foray at the race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The 17/50 had a 2.4-litre sleeve-valve engine with a Cozette supercharger.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The car was prepared at Tim Birkin's race-garage in London.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Aston Martin returned to Le Mans after a three-year hiatus with a works team of three cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The 1.5-litre International was still in a limited run and only seven racing chassis had been made.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Le Mans winner Sammy Davis was in hospital after a major accident at Brooklands at Easter so company engineer Augustus "Bert" Bertelli instead drove with Maurice Harvey.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Former Lea-Francis drivers Kenneth Peacock and Sammy Newsome had the second car while Jack Bezzant and Humphrey Cook had the third.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Voiturette racing was still popular and encouraged enthusiast engineers to make their own small customised specials.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] A mechanic and driver at Salmson, he adapted a Salmson chassis with the oft-used 1.1-litre Ruby engine that put out 35 bhp.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] After successes in the Bol d'Or, Roger Labric encouraged him to enter the Le Mans race and offered to enter two under his name.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] After a disappointing race for BNC the previous year, when the new car didn't even turn a wheel, the team returned with the tried and tested 527 Sport, also with a Ruby engine.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In 1930 George Eyston had approached Cecil Kimber, managing director of MG Cars, about developing the first 750cc car to break the 100mph barrier.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In part, this was because his Land Speed Record rival, Malcolm Campbell was working with Austin for the same goal.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] With the resulting EX120 special, Eyston achieved the record in February 1931 at Montlhéry.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Using the prototype's engine and frame, MG built the new C-Type.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Fourteen cars, already pre-sold, were quickly built in time to take a clean sweep, first time out, at the Brooklands Double-12 (Britain's annual 24-hour event) in May.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The result was repeated a month later at the Irish Grand Prix.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] A week later, two of the cars were entered for Le Mans, without superchargers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Francis Samuelson returned with his regular co-driver (and MG tester) Freddie Kindell, while *Lady* Joan Chetwynd ran her husband's car along with fellow C-Type owner Henry Stisted.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] A number of teams and drivers were racing the weekend before at events across Europe, which made preparations difficult.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Arthur Fox, in one of his Talbots, gave Alfa drivers Birkin, Howe and Campari a lift to London from Dublin where they had all been racing in the Irish Grand Prix meeting.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] After their races the Bugatti team drove their cars across from Molsheim in eastern France, arriving on Thursday.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In practice, one of the cars blew a rear tyre, so team manager "Meo" Costantini directed the drivers to not go above 4000rpm to limit their top speed for the first six hours.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Through practice, the Alfa Romeos had engine ignition problems because of the hybrid fuel being used.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This had happened the year before to Birkin and his "Blower Bentleys".
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] His solution then was to switch to pure benzole and change out the pistons.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Parts were delayed coming from the factory in Milan, the mechanics worked through the night but by race morning only three of the cars were ready.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Team manager Aldo Giovannini stood down Campari and Minoia and instead teamed up Marinoni (as a very competent mechanic in his own right) with Zehender.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The ACO celebrated its Silver Jubilee, formed in 1906 running the first French Grand Prix.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Special guests at the Saturday luncheon included Ferenc Szisz and Felice Nazzaro who had finished first and second respectively at that inaugural event.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] ACO Club secretary, Georges Durand, had also served 25 years and was the honorary starter for the race on a hot, sunny Saturday afternoon.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] First away from the flagfall at 4pm were the two Chryslers, however their lead was short-lived and with the big cars' sluggish acceleration out of the Pontlieue corners, they were overtaken by the works Bugattis of Chiron and Divo.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Henri Stoffel wound up the Mercedes' supercharger and quickly blasted past all four of them into the lead– Chiron failed his breaking at Mulsanne on lap 3 trying to outbrake him and ended up down the escape road.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The two Alfas, and the Bugattis of Rost and Louis-Dreyfus filled out the top-9.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] A bit further back the three Aston Martins were jockeying with the Lorraine while the Chryslers slipped back.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] After an hour though, by lap ten, it was all change.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Birkin had just come in with a misfiring sparkplug when both Stoffel and Chiron arrived with flat tyres.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This put Marinoni's Alfa in the lead, followed by the Bugattis of Divo and Rost.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In his race back up the field Chiron had a big moment halfway down the Hunaudières straight.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Having just overtaken Birkin, the other rear tyre blew at top speed putting him in a wild slide.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] With skill, he regained control and managed to get the car slowly back to the pits.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The two Chryslers were the first retirements.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Sommer was out after 14 laps with a holed radiator, and then five laps later, into the pits came Costier with the same problem.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] At 6.30pm Marinoni had just finished his 20th lap, leading from Divo but Rost, running third, did not come around.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] He had been going down the back straight at 175 kp/h when a tyre blew.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The car crashed through the roadside fence and trees.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Three men standing in the spectator-prohibited zone were run down and one, Jules Bourgoin, was killed while the other two were seriously injured.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Rost had been thrown from the car and suffered head injuries and a broken shoulder and ribs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] So, after three hours, at the first round of pit-stops, Divo led from Marinoni and Stoffel, having all done 23 laps.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Chiron was a lap behind with the two Talbots.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Chiron then pitted with a third delaminated tyre.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Bouriat, who had just taken over from Divo was called in soon after while leading and both remaining works Bugattis were withdrawn, despite boos from the spectators.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This left the Mercedes to battle the Alfa Romeos.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] But when tyre-delaminations struck them twice, the drivers decided to ease back and change tyres every hour to avoid further issues.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] These delays cost the Mercedes eight laps.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Talbots' reliability kept them in touch with the leaders, only doing their first pit-stops at 8pm, four hours into the race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was unknown why Odette Siko bought her Bugatti in for its second stop after 38 laps, but when the team refuelled it two laps before regulations allowed, they were disqualified.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] As dusk fell, Couper's Bentley broke its crankcase just as he was braking for the corners at Pontlieue.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The driver managed to stop just in front of the barriers blocking the main road into Le Mans Going into the night, Marinoni/Zehender were still leading.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] At the 6-hour mark (10pm) they had done 46 laps.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Howe and Birkin were closing in quickly, eventually overtaking them after midnight.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Just a lap back was the Talbot of Rose-Richards/Saunders-Davies while the Lewis/Hindmarsh sister-car had been delayed by electrical issues and now three laps behind them with the Mercedes half a lap further back.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The three Astons were also still running together inside the top-10: Bezzant/Cook in 6th (40 laps) and Bertelli/Harvey in 7th.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] However the team had replaced their headlamps with heavier Zeiss headlamps.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The strain from the roads gradually shook the bolts loose and all the Aston Martins lost time getting them re-secured.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Caban of Labric/Giraud-Cabantous got beached at Pontlieue after midnight, losing much time getting dug out.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Then at 2.30am, a violent lightning flash and thunderclap heralded a short intense squall that flooded the track for an hour.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Cars quickly came into the pits to raise wind-screens and put on wet-weather gear.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] But on his out-lap, Zehender aquaplaned off at Indianapolis corner, slamming the front corner.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] It got repaired and back on the road, but lost four laps.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The two Fox & Nicholl Talbots were still running reliably in third and fourth – their only issues were similar to the Aston Martins.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Both cars each had one of their headlamp brackets break.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The drivers latched onto faster cars, using them as spotters through the night on the dark roads.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] As dawn broke nearly half the field had retired or been withdrawn.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Howe and Birkin had done 92 laps, four laps ahead of Marinoni/Zehender with the two Talbots a further two laps back.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Not long after 6am the rear-axle broke on the works Alfa in second, forcing its retirement.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The MG of Samuelson/Kindell smacked an earth-bank avoiding another car.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] They lost three-quarters an hour fixing the suspension.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ivanowski was able to get hold of some Dunlop tyres to replace his problematic Engleberts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] With the supercharger running, he was soon putting in very quick times, setting the fastest lap of the race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] He was able to overhaul one of the Talbots and got a lap back off the leaders.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] At 9am, the Bezzant/Cook Aston Martin still running in fifth broke a front-wing support and the wing fell off.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Without parts no repairs were possible, and the car was retired.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Around 9.30am, Lewis noticed the Talbot's rear fueltank shifting on the chassis.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Pitting, the team found the frame had cracked just above the rear axle.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite twenty minutes of repairs (using belts and straps to tie the tank in place) and three more laps, it was still dangerously loose, and the car had to be retired.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The metal fatigue was put down to the combined strain from this race and the recent Brooklands Double-12 it had run in.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] This moved the Mercedes up into second, a place it held for the rest of the race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The two little Cabans had quietly kept circulating at a regular rate at the tail of the field, designed to get them to their target distance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] But during the morning, Caban's car came to a stop on the Mulsanne straight with fuel-feed issues.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Going into the afternoon there were only nine cars left running.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The last Bugatti had just retired – the privateer entry of Jean Sébilleau lost its failing clutch.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although the privateer Alfa had a sizeable lead over the Mercedes, they were not able to ease off, as the Talbot (in third) kept up the pressure for honours in the Index and Biennial Cup handicap competitions.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the end, the hard driving by Howe and Birkin gave them a comfortable seven-lap victory, and they were only the second crew to win all three prizes: outright distance, Index and the Coupe Bienniale.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was Birkin's second win after his victory in 1929 with Bentley.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] They also gave Italy its first win in the endurance event, earning personal congratulations from Mussolini.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Their total distance covered broke the 3,000 km (1,900 mi) barrier for the first time.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Mercedes lasted the distance, finishing four laps ahead of the Talbot of Rose-Richards/Saunders-Davies.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Fourth, 23 laps further back, was the old Lorraine-Dietrich.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] It had spent most of the race mixing it with the Aston Martins, with newer engines half its size.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the end it covered two more laps, but 100km less, than its stable-mate that had won the 1926 race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The remaining two Aston Martins had varying stories: Peacock & Newsome retired with less than two hours to go because of bodywork issues while the other, after the assorted delays, had to hurry on to make its target distance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] "Bert" Bertelli and Maurice Harvey made it by just one lap, finishing fifth and winning the 1500cc class.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The little Caban of Vernet/Vallon was the final classified car, just meeting its target by bare metres and over 900km behind the winner.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The meagre six finishers being the lowest number in the history of the race.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The hard-luck story was the Samuelson/Kindell MG.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] With just over an hour to go, a conrod broke.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] The team isolated the affected cylinder and parked the car to rejoin the race just before 4pm to complete a final, careful lap.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Regulations stipulated the last lap had to be done within 30 minutes but when Samuelson took 32 minutes to complete it they were left unclassified.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Alfa Romeo developed the successful 8C-2300 into a shorter, Grand-Prix version developing 180 bhp.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] After a great win in the year's 10-hour Italian Grand Prix, it gained the "Monza" moniker.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Bugatti instead chose to mothball their Type 50s, to concentrate on the more successful Type 51, while the engines were fitted to the new Type 54.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] In a busy month after the race, Ivanowski and Stoffel took the Mercedes successively to the 10-hour French Grand Prix (DNF), Spa 24 Hours (DNF) and Belgian Grand Prix (5th).
[src:chrysler-imperial/1931-24-hours-of-le-mans] Results taken from Quentin Spurring's book, officially licensed by the ACO Class Winners are in **Bold** text.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] King George VI and Queen Elizabeth made their visit to Canada from 17 May to 15 June 1939.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Taking place in the months leading up to the Second World War, the tour was undertaken to strengthen trans-Atlantic support for the United Kingdom in anticipation of a potential war while also showcasing Canada's status as an independent Dominion of the British Empire.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and Queen arrived in Canada by ship, and travelled up the St.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Lawrence River to Quebec City before heading west by rail.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Accompanied throughout by Canadian Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, they visited most major cities across Canada, reaching as far west as Victoria, British Columbia.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] On their return journey east, they briefly travelled to the United States for a state visit and a meeting with President Franklin D.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The royal tour concluded with visits to the Maritimes, after which they departed from Halifax for a tour of the then separate Dominion of Newfoundland.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Although royal family members had previously toured Canada, the 1939 royal tour marked the first time a reigning monarch of Canada visited North America, garnering significant attention from both the public and the media.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Elizabeth's mother had died in 1938, and so Norman Hartnell designed an all-white wardrobe for her delayed state visit to France that year.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] In Canada in 1939 she wore elements of this white mourning, which forms a distinctive feature of the black and white photographs of the tour.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The first portion of the royal tour occurred from 17 May 1939, when the royal couple arrived in Quebec City, to 7 June 1939, when George VI and Mackenzie King departed Canada to conduct a state visit to the United States.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The first portion of the Canadian royal tour, saw the royal couple visit every province in Canada, excluding the provinces in Atlantic Canada, which was toured following George VI and Mackenzie King's return from the United States on 12 June.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The king and queen took up residence at La Citadelle, where the King performed his first official tasks, amongst which was the acceptance of the credentials of Daniel Calhoun Roper as the American envoy to Canada.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King also held the audience with Quebeckers in the Legislative Council chamber of the Parliament Building.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The royal party traveled to Ottawa on 20 May, where the Queen laid the cornerstone of the Supreme Court building.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] There, the King personally granted royal assent to nine bills in the traditional manner which was still being used in Canada at the time – in the United Kingdom, Royal Assent has not been granted by the Sovereign in person since 1854.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] On Parliament Hill, the King's official Canadian birthday (known today as Victoria Day) was marked for the first time with a traditional Trooping of the Colour.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Because he attended this parade instead of the annual trooping on Horse Guards Parade, the one in London was presided by Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Queen Elizabeth and Governor General Lord Tweedsmuir watched the parade from East Block.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King was accompanied at the reviewing box by Prime Minister Mackenzie King, Minister of National Defence Ian Alistair Mackenzie and the Chief of the General Staff, Lieutenant General Ernest Charles Ashton.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The trooping saw members of the Governor General's Foot Guards from Ottawa and the Canadian Grenadier Guards from Montreal, both of which make up the Brigade of Canadian Guards, parade before the King.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] After two days in Ottawa, the royal couple began travelling westward.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The couple travelled to Toronto on 22 May, where they attended the King's Plate horse race and dedicated Coronation Park.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The couple dedicated the soon-to-be completed Rainbow Bridge at Niagara Falls, and unveiled a monument at the site to mark the occasion.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] They also inaugurated the Queen Elizabeth Way (which was named for George's royal consort) as well as various monuments along the route, including a set of decorative stone pillars on the eastern approach to the Henley Bridge in St.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The Royal Train was operated by the Canadian Pacific Railway on the western leg of the tour and the couple continued to be greeted by throngs of Canadians, even in the immigrant-rich but Depression-battered Prairies.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The couple visited Winnipeg and Brandon on 24 May.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] While staying at Government House in Winnipeg, the King made his longest-ever radio broadcast to the British Empire; the table at which he sat remains in the Aides Room of the royal residence.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Then, Prime Minister Mackenzie King described the arrival of the royal train at Brandon: "Wonderful cheering.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] A long bridge overhead crowded with people.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Continuing westward across the Prairies, the Royal Train arrived in Regina on 25 May, followed by Calgary on 26 May and Banff on 27 May.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] After some conventional compliments on the turnout of the escort, the King had said that he had not expected either such crowds or a ceremonial military welcome.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] When he had asked Mackenzie King what to expect in Calgary, the Prime Minister has said it was only a small place of little consequence and that there would not be much there.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] When he saw the guard of honour waiting on the platform, he realized that he should have been in uniform and went back inside the train.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] But it was, of course, too late to change.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] (Major) Bradbrooke got the impression that the King was not at all pleased with his Canadian Prime Minister's advice that day.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] In Banff, Their Majesties and Mackenzie King posed for press photographs at the Banff Springs Hotel.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and Queen also attended a private service at St George-in-the-Pines Anglican church.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and the Queen stopped in Vancouver, Victoria, and a number of other smaller communities in British Columbia.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Mackenzie King was enthused, stating in his diary on 29 May 1939, "the day in Vancouver was one of the finest on the entire tour," and, the following day: "Without question, Victoria has left the most pleasing of all impressions.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] At one night time stop in the Rocky Mountains, the royal couple sang along with an impromptu a cappella rendition of "When the Moon Comes over the Mountain" that broke out amongst the gathered crowd when the moon emerged from behind the clouds.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The royal train arrived in the town of Melville at 10 pm on 3 June, attracting over 60,000 people to the town of 3,000.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The stop was meant to last only ten minutes, after which the train would stay overnight for servicing.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] But, with the throngs of people who arrived, the royal party decided to extend the visit to a half-hour, after which the train pulled away, returning a few hours later, once the crowds had dispersed; Canadian Press reporter R.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Another factor, however, was public relations; the presence of the King and Queen, in both Canada and the United States, was calculated to shore up sympathy for Britain in anticipation of hostilities with Nazi Germany.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The itinerary included visits to Mount Vernon on 9 June, the 1939 New York World's Fair on 10 June, and dinner at Roosevelt's estate at Hyde Park on 11 June, at which President Roosevelt served hot dogs, smoked turkey, and strawberry shortcake to the royal couple.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The 2012 film *Hyde Park on Hudson* starring Bill Murray contains a lengthy fictionalized depiction of the royal couple's visit to the Roosevelt estate.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] On 12 June the royal couple returned to Canada to continue their royal tour of the country, visiting the Maritime provinces.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and the Queen stopped in Doaktown, New Brunswick, to take tea in a local tearoom.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] While they were expected for lunch, they were not expected in the kitchen afterwards, and they took the staff by surprise.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] After a visit to Charlottetown, Prince Edward Island, the royal couple ended their tour at Halifax, Nova Scotia, on 15 June, where a farewell luncheon was held, and the King and Queen each delivered a speech of thanks.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] She was accompanied by British warships and our own destroyers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The *Bluenose* and other vessels also in the harbour as a sort of escort....
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] The King and Queen were at the very top of the ship and kept waving....
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] John's, Newfoundland, George VI and Elizabeth returned to the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] Elizabeth told Canadian Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, "that tour made us", and she returned to Canada frequently both on official tours and privately.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] During another tour of Canada in 1985, Queen Elizabeth, by then the Queen Mother, said, "it is now some 46 years since I first came to this country with the King, in those anxious days shortly before the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] I shall always look back upon that visit with feelings of affection and happiness.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] For the visit the Canadian government issued its second commemorative silver dollar, this one showing the standard picture of the king on the obverse and the Canadian Parliament building on the reverse.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] With a mintage of 1,363,816—large for the time—it remains readily available.
[src:chrysler-imperial/1939-royal-tour-of-canada] At the same time a set of three postage stamps were issued by Canada, two showing members of the Royal Family and one a war memorial.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] The **AACA Museum** is a transportation museum located in Hershey, Pennsylvania, in the United States.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] It is a 501(c)(3) non-profit museum dedicated to the preservation of American automobile history.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Despite its name the museum is not affiliated with the Antique Automobile Club of America.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] The 71,000 square feet (6,600 m2) museum displays over 130 cars, buses, motorcycles, and automobile collectibles in themed settings from the 1890s–1980s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] It is an affiliate museum of the Smithsonian Institution, and the American Alliance of Museums.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Its major collections include the Cammack Tucker Collection, the world's most extensive collection of Tucker automobiles, and the Museum of Bus Transportation collection.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] In 2014, the museum won the NAAMY Award of Excellence from the National Association of Automobile Museums.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] The AACA Museum holds the largest permanent collection of Tucker 48 automobiles in the world.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Named for David Cammack, a historian and collector of Tucker automobiles, the entire collection was donated to the AACA Museum from Cammack's personal collection upon his death in 2013.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Alongside the AACA grand opening in 2003, the Museum of Bus Transportation leased space in the museum's lower level to showcase their collection of 22 classic buses.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] As of 2020, the Museum of Bus Transportation owns roughly 33 buses, most of which are on display in the AACA Museum.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] AACA Museum, Inc. was formed in 1993 as a public charitable organization with a mission to construct a museum to preserve all forms of historical motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] In 1996, the incorporation purchased 25 acres of land in Hershey, Pennsylvania to be used as the site for the future museum building.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Initial costs for the building were estimated at $11 million, and in 2000, the William J.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Cammack Supporting Organization Trust pledged a multi-million dollar testamentary commitment, along with three 1947 Tucker Torpedo automobiles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Much of the rest of the fundraising was accomplished during the AACA annual car shows hosted in Hershey, Pennsylvania.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] The museum opened on June 26, 2003, with roughly 70 cars donated, or on loan from, the club's members.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] Rather than display their cars in long rows, the AACA Museum incorporated an educational approach in its displays by adding scenery and set designs that complement the period in which each car was built.
[src:chrysler-imperial/aaca-museum] In 2013, the museum was named as one of the 12 car museums in the USA worth a detour by MSNBC.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Beginning in 1917, Nimitz was the Navy's leading developer of underway replenishment techniques, the tool which during the Pacific war would allow the American fleet to operate away from port almost indefinitely.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The chief of the Navy's Bureau of Navigation from 1939 to 1942, Nimitz served as the chief of naval operations from 1945 until 1947.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] He was the United States' last surviving officer who served in the rank of fleet admiral.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The USS *Nimitz* supercarrier, the lead ship of her class, is named after Nimitz.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz, a German Texan, was born the son of Anna Josephine (née Henke) and Chester Bernhard Nimitz on 24 February 1885, in Fredericksburg, Texas, where his grandfather's hotel is now the National Museum of the Pacific War.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] His frail, rheumatic father had died six months earlier, on 14 August 1884.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] He was significantly influenced by his German-born paternal grandfather, Charles Henry Nimitz, a former seaman in the German Merchant Marine, who taught Nimitz, "the sea – like life itself – is a stern taskmaster.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The best way to get along with either is to learn all you can, then do your best and don't worry – especially about things over which you have no control".
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] His grandfather had become a Texas Ranger in the Texas Mounted Volunteers in 1851 and later served as captain of the Gillespie Rifles Company in the Confederate States Army during the Civil War.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Originally, Nimitz applied to West Point in hopes of becoming an Army officer, but no appointments were available.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Slayden, US Representative for Texas's 12th congressional district, told Nimitz that he had one appointment available for the United States Naval Academy and that he would award it to the best-qualified candidate.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz felt that this was his only opportunity for further education and spent extra time studying to earn the appointment.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz was appointed to the Naval Academy by Slayden in 1901, and graduated with distinction on 30 January 1905, seventh in a class of 114.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz joined the battleship USS Ohio (BB-12) in San Francisco, and cruised on her to the Far East.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In September 1906, he was transferred to the cruiser *Baltimore*; on 31 January 1907, after the two years at sea as a warrant officer then required by law, Nimitz was commissioned as an ensign.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Remaining on Asiatic Station in 1907, he successively served on the gunboat *Panay*, destroyer *Decatur*, and cruiser *Denver*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The destroyer *Decatur* ran aground on a mud bank in the Philippines on 7 July 1908, while under the command of Ensign Nimitz.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The incident was the result of a navigational error.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz had failed to check the harbor's tide tables and tried Batangas' harbor when the water level was low, leaving *Decatur* stuck until the tide rose again the next morning, and she was pulled free by a small steamer.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Following the grounding, a naval board of inquiry was convened to investigate the circumstances.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The board found that Nimitz had indeed made an error in judgment, and he received a letter of reprimand.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz returned to the United States on board USS *Ranger* when that vessel was converted to a school ship, and in January 1909, began instruction in the First Submarine Flotilla.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In May of that year, he was given command of the flotilla, with additional duty in command of USS *Plunger*, later renamed *A-1*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz was promoted directly from ensign to lieutenant in January 1910.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] He commanded USS *Snapper* (later renamed *C-5*) when that submarine was commissioned on 2 February 1910, and on 18 November 1910, assumed command of USS *Narwhal* (later renamed *D-1*).
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In the latter command, Nimitz had additional duty on 10 October 1911, as Commander 3rd Submarine Division Atlantic Torpedo Fleet.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In November 1911, he was ordered to the Boston Navy Yard, to assist in fitting out USS *Skipjack* and assumed command of that submarine, which had been renamed *E-1*, at her commissioning on 14 February 1912.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On the monitor *Tonopah* (then employed as a submarine tender) on 20 March 1912, Nimitz rescued Fireman Second Class W.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Walsh from drowning, receiving a Silver Lifesaving Medal for his action.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] After commanding the Atlantic Submarine Flotilla from May 1912 to March 1913, Nimitz supervised the building of diesel engines for the fleet oil tanker *Maumee*, under construction at the New London Ship and Engine Company, Groton, Connecticut.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In the summer of 1913, Nimitz (who spoke fluent German) studied engines at the Maschinenfabrik-Augsburg-Nürnberg (M.A.N.) diesel engine plants in Nuremberg, Germany, and Ghent, Belgium.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Returning to the New York Navy Yard, he became executive and engineer officer of *Maumee* at her commissioning on 23 October 1916.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] After the United States declared war on Germany in April 1917, Nimitz was chief engineer of *Maumee* while the vessel served as a refueling ship for the first squadron of US Navy destroyers to cross the Atlantic, to take part in the war.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Under his supervision, *Maumee* conducted the first-ever underway refuelings.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 10 August 1917, Nimitz became aide to Rear Admiral Samuel S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Robison, Commander, Submarine Force, US Atlantic Fleet (ComSubLant).
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 6 February 1918, Nimitz was appointed chief of staff and was awarded a Letter of Commendation for meritorious service as COMSUBLANT's chief of staff.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 16 September, he reported to the office of the Chief of Naval Operations, and on 25 October, was given additional duty as senior member, Board of Submarine Design.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] From May 1919 to June 1920, Nimitz served as executive officer of the battleship *South Carolina*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] He then commanded the cruiser *Chicago* with additional duty in command of Submarine Division 14, based at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz, assisted by four earnest Chief Petty Officers, supervised the construction of Submarine Base Pearl Harbor on a triangle-shaped, overgrown piece of land at the juncture of Southeast Loch and Quarry Loch, and served as the base's first commanding officer.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] During this tour, he also conducted an investigation into the R-14 sailing incident.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz's handling of the disciplinary action in the aftermath of the investigation was considered a model of even-handed fairness, cementing his reputation as a solid and capable leader.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Returning to the mainland in the summer of 1922, Nimitz studied at the Naval War College, Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In June 1923, Nimitz became aide and assistant chief of staff to the Commander, Battle Fleet, and later to the Commander in Chief, United States Fleet.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In August 1926, he went to the University of California, Berkeley, where he established one of the first Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps units and successfully advocated for the program's expansion.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz lost part of his left ring finger in an accident with a diesel engine, saving the rest of it only when the machine briefly jammed against his Annapolis ring.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In June 1929, Nimitz took command of Submarine Division 20.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In June 1931, he assumed command of the destroyer tender *Rigel* and the destroyers out of commission at San Diego, California.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In October 1933, Nimitz took command of the cruiser *Augusta* and deployed to the Far East, where in December, *Augusta* became the flagship of the Asiatic Fleet.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] While in command of the *Augusta,* his legal aide was Chesty Puller.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In April 1935, Nimitz returned home for three years as assistant chief of the Bureau of Navigation, before becoming commander, Cruiser Division 2, Battle Force.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In September 1938, Nimitz took command of Battleship Division 1, Battle Force.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] During this time, he conducted experiments in the underway refueling of large ships which would prove a key element in the Navy's success in the war to come.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] "Tests were planned for the spring of 1939 [June 1939] using elements of the fleet left on the West Coast while the rest of the fleet was in the Caribbean participating in Fleet Problem XX.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz was scheduled to remain on the West Coast aboard his flagship the *Arizona*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The aircraft carrier *Saratoga*, the heavy cruisers *Chester* and *Vincennes*, and the light cruiser *Trenton* would also be left behind.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] These ships, with their escorts and at least one oiler, would constitute Task Force 7.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 15 June 1939, Nimitz was appointed chief of the Bureau of Navigation.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] From 1940 to 1941, he served as president of the Army Navy Country Club, in Arlington, Virginia.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Ten days after the attack on Pearl Harbor on 7 December 1941, Rear Admiral Nimitz was selected by President Franklin D.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Roosevelt to be the commander-in-chief of the United States Pacific Fleet (CINCPACFLT).
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz immediately departed Washington for Hawaii and took command in a ceremony on the top deck of the submarine *Grayling*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] He was promoted to the rank of admiral, effective 31 December 1941, upon assuming command.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The change of command ceremony would normally have taken place aboard a battleship, but every battleship in Pearl Harbor had been either sunk or damaged during the attack.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Assuming command at the most critical period of the war in the Pacific, Admiral Nimitz organized his forces to halt the Japanese advance, despite the shortage of ships, planes, and supplies.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz had a significant advantage in that the United States had cracked the Japanese diplomatic code and had made progress on the naval code JN-25.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The Japanese had kept radio silence before the attack on Pearl Harbor, although events were then moving so rapidly that they had to rely on coded radio messages they did not realize were being read in Hawaii.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 24 March 1942, the newly formed US-British Combined Chiefs of Staff issued a directive designating the Pacific theater an area of American strategic responsibility.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Six days later, the US Joint Chiefs of Staff (JCS) divided the theater into three areas: the Pacific Ocean Areas, the Southwest Pacific Area (commanded by General Douglas MacArthur), and the Southeast Pacific Area.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The JCS designated Nimitz as "Commander in Chief, Pacific Ocean Areas", with operational control over all Allied units (air, land, and sea) in that area.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz, in Hawaii, and his superior Admiral Ernest King, the Chief of Naval Operations, in Washington, rejected the plan of General Douglas MacArthur to advance on Japan through New Guinea and the Philippines and Formosa.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Instead, they proposed an island-hopping plan that would allow them to bypass most of the Japanese strength in the Central Pacific until they reached Okinawa.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] President Roosevelt compromised, giving both MacArthur and Nimitz their own theaters.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The two Pacific theaters were favored, to the dismay of generals George Marshall and Dwight Eisenhower, who favored a Germany-first strategy.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] King and Nimitz provided MacArthur with some naval forces but kept most of the carriers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] However, when the time came to plan an invasion of Japan, MacArthur was given overall command.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz faced superior Japanese forces at the crucial defensive actions of the Battle of the Coral Sea and the Battle of Midway.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The Battle of the Coral Sea, while a loss in terms of total damage suffered, has been described as resulting in the strategic success of turning back an apparent Japanese invasion of Port Moresby on the island of New Guinea.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Two Japanese carriers were temporarily taken out of action in the battle, which would deprive the Japanese of their use in the Midway operation that shortly followed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The Navy's intelligence team reasoned that the Japanese would be attacking Midway, so Nimitz moved all his available forces to the defense.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The severe losses in Japanese carriers at Midway affected the balance of naval air power during the remainder of 1942 and were crucial in neutralizing Japanese offensive threats in the South Pacific.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Naval engagements during the Battle of Guadalcanal left both forces severely depleted.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] However, with the allied advantage in land-based air-power, the results were sufficient to secure Guadalcanal.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The US and allied forces then undertook to neutralize remaining Japanese offensive threats with the Solomon Islands campaign and the New Guinea campaign, while building capabilities for major fleet actions.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In 1943, Midway became a forward submarine base, greatly enhancing US capabilities against Japanese shipping.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In terms of combat, 1943 was a relatively quiet year, but it proved decisive inasmuch as Nimitz gained the materiel and manpower needed to launch major fleet offensives to destroy Japanese power in the central Pacific region.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] This drive opened with the Gilbert and Marshall Islands campaign from November 1943 to February 1944, followed by the destruction of the strategic Japanese base at Truk Lagoon, and the Marianas campaign that brought the Japanese homeland within range of new strategic bombers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz's forces inflicted a decisive defeat on the Japanese fleet in the Battle of the Philippine Sea (19–20 June 1944), which allowed the capture of Saipan, Guam, and Tinian.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] His Fleet Forces isolated enemy-held bastions on the central and eastern Caroline Islands and secured in quick succession Peleliu, Angaur, and Ulithi.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In the Philippines, his ships destroyed much of the remaining Japanese naval power at the Battle of Leyte Gulf, that lasted from 24 to 26 October 1944.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] With the loss of the Philippines, Japan's energy supply routes from Indonesia came under direct threat, crippling their war effort.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] By act of Congress, passed on 14 December 1944, the rank of fleet admiral – the highest rank in the Navy – was established.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] The next day, President Franklin Roosevelt appointed Nimitz to that rank.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz took the oath of that office on 19 December.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In January 1945, Nimitz moved the headquarters of the Pacific Fleet forward from Pearl Harbor to Guam for the remainder of the war.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz's wife remained in the continental United States for the duration of the war and did not join her husband in Hawaii or Guam.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In 1945, Nimitz's forces launched successful amphibious assaults on Iwo Jima and Okinawa and his carriers raided the home waters of Japan.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In addition, Nimitz also arranged for the Army Air Force to mine the Japanese ports and waterways by air with B-29 Superfortresses in a successful mission called Operation Starvation, which severely interrupted Japanese logistics.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 2 September 1945, Nimitz signed as representative of the United States when Japan formally surrendered on board USS *Missouri* in Tokyo Bay.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 5 October 1945, which had been officially designated as "Nimitz Day" in Washington, D.C., Nimitz was personally presented a second Gold Star for the third award of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal by President Harry S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Truman "for exceptionally meritorious service as Commander in Chief, U.S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Pacific Fleet and Pacific Ocean Areas, from June 1944 to August 1945".
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] On 26 November 1945, Nimitz's nomination as Chief of Naval Operations (CNO) was confirmed by the US Senate, and on 15 December, he relieved Fleet Admiral Ernest J.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz had assured the President that he was willing to serve as the CNO for one two-year term, but no longer.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz tackled the difficult task of reducing the most powerful navy in the world to a fraction of its war-time strength while establishing and overseeing active and reserve fleets with the strength and readiness required to support national policy.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] For the postwar trial of German Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz at the Nuremberg Trials in 1946, Nimitz furnished an affidavit in support of the practice of unrestricted submarine warfare, a practice that he himself had employed throughout the war in the Pacific.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] This evidence is widely credited as a reason why Dönitz was sentenced to only 10 years of imprisonment.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz endorsed an entirely new course for the US Navy's future by way of supporting then-Captain Hyman G.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Rickover's chain-of-command-circumventing proposal in 1947 to build USS *Nautilus*, the world's first nuclear-powered vessel.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] As is noted at a display at the Nimitz Museum in Fredericksburg, Texas: "Nimitz's greatest legacy as CNO is arguably his support of Admiral Hyman Rickover's effort to convert the submarine fleet from diesel to nuclear propulsion".
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz retired from office as CNO on 15 December 1947, and received a third Gold Star in lieu of a fourth Navy Distinguished Service Medal.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] However, since the rank of fleet admiral is a lifetime appointment, he remained on active duty for the rest of his life, with full pay and benefits.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz and his wife, Catherine, moved to Berkeley, California.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] After suffering a serious fall in 1964, he and Catherine moved to US Naval quarters on Yerba Buena Island in the San Francisco Bay.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In San Francisco, Nimitz served in the mostly ceremonial post as a special assistant to the Secretary of the Navy in the Western Sea Frontier.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] He worked to help restore goodwill with Japan after World War II by helping to raise funds for the restoration of the Japanese Imperial Navy battleship *Mikasa*, Admiral Heihachiro Togo's flagship at the Battle of Tsushima in 1905.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] From 1949 to 1953, Nimitz served as UN-appointed plebiscite administrator for Jammu and Kashmir.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] His proposed role as administrator was accepted by Pakistan but rejected by India.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz became a member of the Bohemian Club of San Francisco.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In 1948, he sponsored a Bohemian dinner in honor of US Army General Mark Clark, known for his campaigns in North Africa and Italy.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz served as a regent of the University of California from 1948 to 1956, where he had formerly been a faculty member as a professor of naval science for the Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps program.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz was honored on 17 October 1964, by the University of California on Nimitz Day.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz married Catherine Vance Freeman (22 March 1892 – 1 February 1979) on 9 April 1913, in Wollaston, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] They had four children together: Catherine Vance "Kate", Chester William "Chet" Jr., Anna Elizabeth "Nancy", and Mary Manson.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Kate graduated from the University of California, Berkeley, in 1934, became a music librarian with the Washington D.C.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Public Library, and married US Navy Commander James Thomas Lay (1909–2001), from St.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Clair, Missouri, in Chester and Catherine's suite at the Fairfax Hotel in Washington, D.C., on 9 March 1945.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] She had met Lay in the summer of 1934 while visiting her parents in Southeast Asia.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Chet graduated from the US Naval Academy in 1936 and served as a submariner in the Navy until his retirement in 1957, reaching the (post-retirement) rank of rear admiral; he served as chairman of PerkinElmer from 1969 to 1980.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nancy was an expert on the Soviet economy at the RAND Corporation from 1952 until her retirement in the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Mary joined the Dominican Sisters of San Rafael, working at the Dominican University of California.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] She taught biology for 16 years and was academic dean for 11 years, acting president for a year, and vice president for institutional research for 13 years before becoming the university's emergency preparedness coordinator.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] She held this job until her death, due to cancer, on 27 February 2006.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In late 1965, Nimitz suffered a stroke, complicated by pneumonia.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] In January 1966, he left the US Naval Hospital (Oak Knoll) in Oakland to return home to his naval quarters.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Nimitz died at home on the evening of 20 February at Quarters One on Yerba Buena Island in San Francisco Bay, four days before his 81st birthday.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] His funeral on 24 February – what would have been his 81st birthday – was at the chapel of adjacent Naval Station Treasure Island, and Nimitz was buried with full military honors at Golden Gate National Cemetery in San Bruno.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] He lies alongside his wife and his lifelong friends Admiral Raymond A.
[src:chrysler-imperial/admiral-chester-nimitz] Lockwood and their wives, an arrangement made by all of them while living.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with an annual household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low rate of air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow by between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona; Hong Kong; China; Japan; and Italy.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Costs of health care can act as another barrier: the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and has encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] The Chinese inventor Ding Huan (1st century CE) of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-imperial/air-conditioning] In the nations of Europe where the technology is relatively unadopted, the strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The **history of Chrysler** involves engineering innovations, high finance, wide alternations of profits and losses, various mergers and acquisitions, and multinationalization.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler, a large automobile manufacturer, was founded in the 1920s and continues under the name Stellantis North America.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler was founded by Walter Chrysler on June 6, 1925, when the Maxwell Motor Company (est.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] 1904) was re-organized into the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Walter Chrysler had originally arrived at the ailing Maxwell-Chalmers company in the early 1920s, having been hired to take over and overhaul the company's troubled operations just after a similar rescue job at the Willys car company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In late 1923, production of the Chalmers automobile was ended.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Then in January 1924, Walter Chrysler launched an eponymous automobile.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Chrysler 70 (also called the B-70) was a 6-cylinder automobile, designed to provide customers with an advanced, well-engineered car at a more affordable price than they might expect.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Elements of this car are traceable back to a prototype which had been under development at Willys at the time Chrysler was there.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The original 1924 Chrysler included a carburetor air filter, high-compression engine, full pressure lubrication inside the engine, and an oil filter, at a time when most autos came without all these features.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Among the innovations in its early years would be the first practical mass-produced four-wheel hydraulic brakes, a system nearly completely engineered by Chrysler with patents assigned to Lockheed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler pioneered rubber engine mounts to reduce vibration; Oilite bearings; and superfinishing for shafts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler also developed a road wheel with a ridged rim, designed to keep a deflated tire from flying off the wheel.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This safety wheel was eventually adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Following the introduction of the Chrysler, the Maxwell marque was dropped after the 1925 model year.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The new, lower-priced 4-cylinder Chrysler introduced for 1926 year was a badge-engineered Maxwell.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The advanced engineering and testing that went into Chrysler Corporation cars helped to push the company to the second-place position in U.S. sales by 1936, a position it would last hold in 1949.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In 1928, Chrysler Corporation began dividing its vehicle offerings by price class and function.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The **Plymouth** brand was introduced at the low priced end of the market created essentially by once again reworking and rebadging Chrysler's 4-cylinder model.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] At the same time, the **DeSoto** marque was introduced in the medium-price field.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Shortly thereafter, Chrysler bought the Dodge Brothers automobile and truck company and launched the Fargo range of trucks.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] By the late 1930s, the DeSoto and **Dodge** divisions would trade places in the corporate hierarchy.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This proliferation of marques under Chrysler's umbrella might have been inspired by the similar strategy employed successfully by General Motors.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Beginning in 1955, **Imperial**, formerly the top model of the Chrysler brand, became a separate make of its own, and in 1960, the Valiant was introduced likewise as a distinct marque.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In the U.S. market, Valiant was made a model in the Plymouth line and the DeSoto make was discontinued for 1961.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] With those exceptions per applicable year and market, Chrysler's range from lowest to highest price from the 1940s through the 1970s was Valiant, Plymouth, Dodge, DeSoto, Chrysler, and Imperial.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] After acquiring AMC in 1987, Chrysler fulfilled one of AMC's conditions of sale by creating the Eagle marque in 1988 to be sold at existing AMC-Jeep dealers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Eagle brand lasted a decade, being discontinued in 1998, while Plymouth was ended three years later.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] By 2001 and as of September 2009, the company had three marques worldwide: Dodge, Jeep, and Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Effective October 2009, however, a fourth brand was established with the creation of the Ram brand, a breakout from the Dodge marque.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Initially, the new brand consisted of the Ram full-size pickup, Dakota compact pickup and the Sprinter van.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] During the unveiling of Chrysler's business plan on November 5, CEO Sergio Marchionne indicated that the Ram brand will be augmented by Fiat-sourced vehicles, including a smaller van than the Sprinter, which itself would be replaced by a Fiat-based vehicle.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In 2011, however, Fiat became Chrysler's fifth brand with the North American introduction of the Fiat 500.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In the 1930s, the company created a formal vehicle parts division under the **MoPar** brand (a portmanteau of **Mo**tor **Par**ts), with the result that "Mopar" remains a colloquial term for vehicles produced by Chrysler Corporation.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The MoPar (later **Mopar**) brand was not used in Canada, where parts were sold under the **Chryco** and **AutoPar** brands, until the Mopar brand was phased into the Canadian market beginning in the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Many Chrysler Corporation vehicle parts also bore variants of the **DPCD** monogram, for *Dodge-Plymouth-Chrysler-DeSoto*, well after the 1961 end of DeSoto production.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler's **Airtemp** marque for stationary and mobile air conditioning, refrigeration, and climate control was launched with the first installation in 1930's Chrysler Building.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Airtemp Corporation was incorporated in 1934 and it utilized a former Maxwell factory.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Airtemp invented capacity regulators, sealed radial compressors, and the self-contained air conditioning system, along with a superior high-speed radial compressor, and by 1941 had over 500 dealers selling its air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The company supplied medical refrigeration units in World War II, and dominated the industry in the 1940s but slowly fell behind.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] By the 1970s Airtemp was losing money and was sold to Fedders in 1976.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In 2012 the name was reborn as a Nordyne byproduct exclusively sold by the R.E.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In the 1980s, Chrysler formed a subsidiary business called **Acustar** to sell parts to other automakers as well as supplying parts for Chrysler-built vehicles, similar to General Motors' creation of Delphi Corporation and Ford's later creation of Visteon.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In 1934, the company introduced the Airflow models, featuring an advanced streamlined body, among the first to be designed using aerodynamic principles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler created the industry's first wind tunnel to develop them.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Buyers rejected its styling, and the more conventionally designed Dodge and Plymouth cars pulled the firm through the Depression years.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Plymouth was one of only a few marques that actually increased sales during the cash-strapped thirties.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The unsuccessful Airflow had a chilling effect on Chrysler styling and marketing, which remained determinedly conservative through the 1940s and into the 1950s, with the single exception of the installation of hidden headlights on the very brief production run of 1942 DeSotos.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Engineering advances continued, and in 1951 the firm introduced the first of a long and famous series of Hemi V8s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In 1955, things brightened with the introduction of Virgil Exner's successful "100 Million Dollar Look", followed in 1956 by Chrysler's pioneering adoption of transistor radios in cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] On April 28, 1955, Chrysler and Philco had announced the development and production of the world's first all-transistor car radio.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Mopar model 914HR was developed and produced by Chrysler and Philco and was a $150.00 "option" on the 1956 Imperial automobile models.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Philco was the company that had manufactured the all-transistor car radio Mopar model 914HR, starting in the fall of 1955 at its Sandusky, Ohio plant, for the Chrysler corporation.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] With the inauguration of the Forward Look cars for 1957, **Torsion-Aire** suspension was introduced.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This was not air suspension but an indirect-acting, torsion-spring front suspension system that drastically reduced unsprung weight and shifted the car's center of gravity downward and rearward.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This resulted in both a smoother ride and significantly improved handling.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] A rush to production of the 1957 models led to quality control problems, including poor body fit and finish, resulting in significant and early rusting.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This, coupled with a national recession, found the company again in recovery mode.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] On September 28, 1957, Chrysler announced the production of electronic fuel injection (EFI) to be available as an option on some of its new 1958 car models (Chrysler 300D, Dodge D500, DeSoto Adventurer, Plymouth Golden Commando V-8) that resulted in approximately 35 total installations.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler used the same all-transistor modulator "Electrojector" fuel injection system from Bendix Corporation that was withdrawn from public sale of the 1957 Rambler Rebel by American Motors because the system could not be made reliable.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Owners of EFI Chryslers were so dissatisfied that all but one were retrofitted with carburetors, while that one has been completely restored, with original EFI electronic problems resolved.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] During World War II, essentially all of Chrysler's facilities were devoted to building military vehicles and systems.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler ranked eighth among United States corporations in the value of wartime production contracts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler made the converters for the Manhattan Project's K-25 gaseous diffusion plant in their Lynch Road plant in Detroit, after Dr Carl Heussner of the Chrysler plating laboratory solved the nickel plating problem.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] One of Chrysler's most significant contributions to the war effort was not in the field of vehicles but in design and manufacture of the components of radar systems.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Radiation Laboratory at MIT, established in 1941 to develop microwave radars, developed the SCR-584, the most widely recognized radar system of the war era.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This system included a parabolic antenna six feet in diameter that was mechanically aimed in a helical pattern (round and round as well as up and down).
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] For the final production design of this antenna and its highly complex drive mechanism, the Army's Signal Corps Laboratories turned to Chrysler's Central Engineering Office.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] There, the parabola was changed from aluminum to steel, allowing production forming using standard automotive presses.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] To keep weight down, 6,000 equally spaced holed were drilled in the face (this did not affect the radiation pattern).
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The drive mechanism was completely redesigned, using technology derived from Chrysler's research in automotive gears and differentials.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The changes resulted in improved performance, reduced weight, and easier maintenance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] A large portion of the Dodge plant was used to build 1,500 of the SCR-584 antennas as well as the vans needed for the system.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] After the war, Chrysler continued with special projects for the U.S. government.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] These were in the aerospace fields of missiles and space boosters.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Army established the Ordnance Guided Missile Center (OGMC) at Redstone Arsenal, adjacent to Huntsville, Alabama.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] To form OGMC, about 1,000 civilian and military personnel were transferred from Fort Bliss, Texas.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Included was a group of German scientists and engineers led by Wernher von Braun; this group had been brought to America under Project Paperclip.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] OGMC designed the Army's first short-range ballistic missile, the PGM-11 Redstone, based on the WWII German V-2 missile.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler established the Missile Division to serve as the Redstone prime contractor, setting up an engineering operation in Huntsville and for production obtaining use from the U.S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Navy of a large plant in Warren, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Redstone was in active service from 1958 to 1964; it was also the first missile to test-launch a live nuclear weapon, first detonated in a 1958 test in the South Pacific.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Working together, the Missile Division and von Braun's team greatly increased the capability of the Redstone, resulting in the PGM-19 Jupiter, a medium-range ballistic missile.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In May 1959, a Jupiter missiles launched two small monkeys into space in a nose cone on a Jupiter; this was America's first successful flight and recovery of live space payloads.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Responsibility for deploying Jupiter missiles was transferred from the Army to the Air Force; armed with nuclear warheads, they were first deployed in Italy and Turkey during the early 1960s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Keller the president and chairman of the board of Chrysler was appointed part-time *Director of Guided Missiles* by President Truman to "make sense" of the missile program.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Kenneth Nichols, who had worked with him on the Manhattan Project, was his assistant.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] They were to select missiles to be put into production and specify the number required and give more priority to air defense missiles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The process of authorizing came to be known as "Kellerizing", and once when the Navy objected to numbers lower than they desired being specified for their missile, Keller refused to accept the Navy letter.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] He sent it back, saying he was willing to discuss the numbers but refused to reply in writing and get into the "Pentagon paper mill procedure" of "endless reviews and letter writing".
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In July 1959, NASA chose the Redstone missile as the basis for the Mercury-Redstone Launch Vehicle to be used for suborbital test flights of the Project Mercury spacecraft.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Three uncrewed MLRV launch attempts were made between November 1960 and March 1961, two of which were successful.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The MLRV successfully launched the chimpanzee Ham and astronauts Alan Shepard and Gus Grissom on three suborbital flights in January, May and July 1961.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] As America's crewed space flight plans became more ambitious, Wernher von Braun's team designed the Saturn family of launch vehicles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] With Chrysler's Huntsville operation then designated the Space Division, Chrysler became Marshall Space Flight Center’s prime contractor for the first (booster) stage of the Saturn I and Saturn IB vehicles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Saturn I booster stage was designated **S-I**, which was upgraded to the S-IB for the Saturn IB.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler based its fuel tank design on a cluster of its Redstone and Jupiter tanks, using four Redstone tanks to hold the RP-1 fuel and four to hold the liquid oxygen (LOX) oxidizer, around a central Jupiter LOX tank.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler built these for the Apollo program in the Michoud Assembly Facility in East New Orleans, one of the largest manufacturing plants in the world.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Between October 1961 and July 1965, NASA launched four S-I boosters with dummy upper stages on suborbital test flights, followed by six complete Saturn Is on uncrewed orbital flights.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The last five of these tested boilerplate Apollo spacecraft, and the last three also carried Pegasus micro meteoroid detection satellites.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Between February 1966 and July 1975, NASA launched nine Saturn IBs on two suborbital flights and seven orbital flights (five of which were crewed); all flights were successful.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] On April 28, 1960, Chrysler president Lester Lum Colbert was elevated to the position of chairman and William C.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Newberg unexpectedly resigned after two months on the job.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] On July 21, 1960, the board of directors announced that it had reached a settlement agreement with Newberg over $450,000 in profits he had made from his stake in two parts suppliers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Minor, was forced to resign from his position as director of marketing for the Plymouth–DeSoto–Valiant division after it was found he received $20,000 in sales commissions on Chrysler contracts from two transportation advertising companies he held ownership in.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] On January 27, 1961, Colbert disclosed that his wife had owned 444 shares in a Chrysler supplier.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] On July 27, 1961, Colbert announced he was resigning as chairman and president "for the good of the corporation".
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] He was succeeded as chairman by George H.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Starting in the 1960 model year, Chrysler built all their passenger cars with Unibody (unit-body or monocoque) construction, except the Imperials which retained body-on-frame construction until 1967.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler thus became the only one of the Big Three American automakers (General Motors Corporation, Ford Motor Company, and Chrysler) to offer unibody construction on the vast majority of their product lines.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This construction technique, now the worldwide standard, offers advantages in vehicle rigidity, handling, and crash safety, while reducing squeak and rattle development as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler's contributions to the technology included the first use of computers to design unit-body cars, and the first setup where exterior sheet metal was not required for structural strength, making sheet metal replacement easier.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler's new compact line, the Valiant, opened strong and continued to gain market share for over a decade.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Valiant was introduced as a marque of its own, but the Valiant line was placed under the Plymouth marque for US-market sales in 1961.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The 1960 Valiant was the first production automobile with an alternator (generating alternating current, paired with diodes for rectification back to direct current) rather than a direct current electrical generator as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] It proved such an improvement that it was used in all Chrysler products in 1961.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The DeSoto marque was withdrawn from the market after the introduction of the 1961 models due in part to the broad array of the Dodge lines and the general neglect of the division.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The same affliction plagued Plymouth as it also suffered when Dodge crept into Plymouth's price range.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] This would eventually lead to the demise of Plymouth several decades later.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] An ill-advised downsizing of the full-size Dodge and Plymouth lines in 1962 hurt sales and profitability for several years.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The company was also the first to use a seven-step rust proofing bath system, though not the first to use rust proofing baths.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In April 1964, the Plymouth Barracuda, a Valiant sub-model, was introduced.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The huge glass rear window and sloping roof were polarizing styling features.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Barracuda was released almost two weeks before Ford's Mustang, making the Barracuda the first pony car.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Even so, the Mustang outsold it 10-to-1 between April 1964 and August 1965.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Perception of the Barracuda as nothing but a reskinned Valiant was not aided by sharing front-end sheet metal.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler's target buyers were obviously men, and attracting female buyers was apparently not a high priority, because a 1967 sales brochure proclaimed, "At last—specifications your wife can understand." (This was, perhaps, an improvement over the Dodge La Femme option of 1955.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] For many years, Chrysler developed gas turbine engines, which are capable of operating on a wide array of combustible fuels, for automotive use.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Turbines were common in military vehicles, and Chrysler built many prototypes for passenger cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In the 1960s, mass production seemed almost ready.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Fifty Chrysler Turbine Cars, specialty designed Ghia-bodied coupes were built in 1962 and placed into the hands of consumers for final testing.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] After further development and testing to make emissions conform to 1970s-enacted EPA standards, the engines were planned as an option for the 1977 model LeBaron.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] However, Chrysler was forced to abandon the turbine engine as a precondition of U.S. government loan guarantees when the company experienced financial difficulties in the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] In the 1960s, Chrysler expanded into Europe, attaining a majority interest in the British Rootes Group in 1964, Simca of France and Barreiros of Spain, to form Chrysler Europe.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] For the Rootes Group, one outcome of this takeover was the launch of the Hillman Avenger in 1970 (briefly sold in the U.S. as the Plymouth Cricket), which sold in Britain alongside the rear-engined Imp and the Hunter.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] During the 1970s the former Rootes Group got into severe financial difficulties.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The Simca and Barreiros divisions were more successful, but in the end the various problems were overwhelming and the firm gained little from these ventures.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] Chrysler sold these assets to PSA Peugeot Citroën in 1978, which in turn sold the British and Spanish truck production lines to Renault of France.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p01] The racing success of several of these models on the NASCAR circuit burnished the company's engineering reputation.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The 1970s were tumultuous for Chrysler since, like all the American car companies of the era, the company was reliant on a marketplace where cheap oil was the norm.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] As market conditions changed and gas prices rose, Chrysler could not adapt in time.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Critics of government regulations have claimed that U.S. anti-trust laws prohibited U.S. automakers from forming Japanese or European-style industry consortiums (which helped these foreign competitors to save costs).
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler was also slow to adapt to a gradual tightening of anti-pollution regulations.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However, given that Chrysler's European divisions already had both the talent and the knowledge to make fuel-economic, less polluting vehicles, all that Chrysler's management had to do was to import European technology that it already owned.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler's American difficulties, therefore, were largely the result of poor management.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler's lower sales volumes meant that new development and implementation costs made up a larger proportion of a vehicle's cost compared to Ford and General Motors.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] To avoid pricing themselves out of the market, Chrysler clumsily detuned its existing engines to meet emission requirements, which resulted in lower fuel economy at a time when fuel prices were rising.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] There was a rush to sell the compact Dodge Dart and Plymouth Valiant, but the 1973 oil crisis sharply reduced demand for the large, fuel-thirsty vehicles Americans had previously bought in large numbers and which made up the bulk of Chrysler's product line.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] At mid-decade, the company scored a conspicuous success with its first entry in the personal luxury car market, the Chrysler Cordoba.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The hurried introduction of the Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volaré in 1976 brought enormous warranty costs to repair faulty design and shoddy construction, and destroyed the longstanding loyalty built up by the Dart and Valiant predecessors.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] At the time, the product recalls for the Aspen and Volare were the largest ever, eclipsed by the GM X-series the following decade.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler Europe essentially collapsed in 1977, and was offloaded to Peugeot the following year, soon after having helped design the new Plymouth Horizon and Dodge Omni.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1980, Chrysler Australia, which was producing the locally developed Chrysler Valiant and the Mitsubishi Galant based Chrysler Sigma, was sold to Mitsubishi Motors and changed its name to Mitsubishi Motors Australia Limited.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The subcompact Horizon/Omni duo was reaching the US market as the second gas crisis struck, and although they sold well, selling over 300,000 units each in their first year, sales of Chrysler's larger cars were slowing, and the company had no strong compact line to fall back on.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Realizing that the company would go out of business if it did not receive a significant amount of money to turn the company around, Iacocca approached the United States Congress on September 7, 1979 and asked for US$1.5 billion in loan guarantees.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Congress reluctantly passed the "Chrysler Corporation Loan Guarantee Act of 1979" Pub.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] 96–185 on December 20, 1979 (signed into law by President Jimmy Carter on January 7, 1980), prodded by Chrysler workers and dealers in every congressional district who feared the loss of their livelihoods.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The military then bought thousands of Dodge pickup trucks which entered military service as the Commercial Utility Cargo Vehicle M-880 Series.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] With such help and a few innovative cars, Chrysler would manage to avoid bankruptcy and slowly recover.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] After receiving this reprieve, Chrysler released the first of the K-Car line, the Dodge Aries and Plymouth Reliant, in 1981.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Like the minivan which would come later, these compact automobiles were based on design proposals that Ford had rejected during Iacocca's (and Sperlich's) tenure there.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Since they were released in the middle of the major 1980–1982 recession, these small, efficient and inexpensive front-wheel drive cars sold rapidly.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Aside from small cars, Iacocca re-introduced the full sized Imperial as a company's flagship.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The new model had all of the newest technologies of the time – including fully electronic fuel injection (the first car in the U.S. to be so equipped) and an all-digital dashboard.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Despite some marketing help from Iacocca's friend Frank Sinatra, including a special edition named after him, the revived Imperial sold poorly, selling only 12,000 cars out of the 25,000 that were originally planned for production.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Imperial was discontinued after the 1983 model year, and is regarded as the last of the ''Malaise era'' automobiles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In February 1982 Chrysler announced the sale of Chrysler Defense, its profitable defense subsidiary to General Dynamics for US$348.5 million.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The sale was completed in March 1982 for the revised figure of US$336.1 million.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1987, it was discovered that Chrysler sold an estimated 32,750 cars that had been test-driven with disconnected odometers – some as much as 500 miles (800 km) – before being shipped to dealers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The controversy gained fire after the United States Senate got involved, as Senator Sam Nunn bought one of the Chryslers in question.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler settled out of court with complainants.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca sought to minimize damage to the corporation's public image by calling a news conference in which he termed the action "dumb" and "unforgivable".
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1987, a joint venture with Mitsubishi Motors called Diamond Star Motors strengthened the company's hand in the small car market, and a new plant in Normal, Illinois was constructed to build the first DSM cars, which were introduced in 1990.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In the same year, Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation (AMC) for $1.5 billion dollars (or $3,577,768,014 in 2021 dollars).
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Although Chrysler received AMC's dealer network and its engineering talent, the main motivations for the buyout were to bring the profitable Jeep brand under the Chrysler umbrella, including the Jeep Grand Cherokee, which AMC had already finished most of the work on, and Iacocca desperately wanted.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The other motivation was the then-new Brampton Assembly plant, which at the time was one of the most advanced vehicle assembly plants in North America, and allowed Chrysler to expand production capacity.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Also AMC's Eagle Premier would form the basis for the future Chrysler LH platform sedans that were produced at Brampton.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] This bolstered the firm's size, but the American Motors purchase was saddled with $900 million in debt.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Also, Chrysler was still the weakest of the Big Three.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] After AMC's buyout, Chrysler insiders speculated that AMC would take over the larger firm from within.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Part of the reason was that AMC's Jeep Cherokee product line alone soon accounted for more than a third of Chrysler's profits.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Several AMC leaders became stars at Chrysler, including François Castaing, AMC's vice president for Product Engineering and Development.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler was suffering a five-year product slump after the success with its small cars and minivans, and by the late 1980s was mainly making K-car derivatives that looked and drove alike.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler was in desperate need to replicate the culture at AMC and Renault where work was conducted in an atmosphere "of constant change." Not only was Castaing made Chrysler's point man for fighting Chrysler's competitors, but he was also called to engineer a variety of products.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler surprised the industry by purchasing Italian sports car maker Lamborghini, with the $25 million acquisition heavily driven by Iacocca.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler executives were appointed to Lamborghini's board, although most of the key members remained.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] To begin its revival, Lamborghini received a cash injection of US$50 million from its new owner, and the slow-selling Jalpa was discontinued.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Lamborghini became profitable, and a more efficient franchise with full service and spare parts support was established, replacing the loosely affiliated and disorganized private dealer network.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler was interested in entering the "extra premium" sports car market, which Chrysler estimated at about 5,000 cars per year, worldwide.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler aimed to produce a car to compete with the Ferrari 328 by 1991, and also wanted the Italians to produce an engine that could be used in a Chrysler car for the American market, which later became the Viper engine.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler also took Lamborghini into motorsport for the first time, and became involved in the design of the Lamborghini Diablo when Chrysler designer Tom Gale restyled Marcello Gandini's original concept for a softer look, which alienated Gandini.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler also previewed the Lamborghini Portofino concept at the Frankfurt Auto show, but it was poorly received by the press and Lamborghini executives.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Although profits increased past the $1 million mark in 1991, the uptick in fortunes was to be brief; in 1992, sales crashed due to the early 1990s recession, and the $239,000 Diablo proved ultimately to be inaccessible to American enthusiasts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] With Lamborghini bleeding money, Chrysler decided that the automaker was no longer producing enough cars to justify its investment, and sold the company to Indonesian conglomerate SEDTCO Pty. for $40 million.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1988, Chrysler and Fiat, owner of Alfa Romeo, reached an agreement that named Chrysler to be the exclusive distributor for Alfa Romeo in North America and easily allow Chrysler dealers to sell Alfa products, which lasted until Alfa left the United States in 1995.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The initial contact between the two firms would lead to high-level talks in 1990 between Iacocca and Fiat Chairman Giovanni Agnelli about establishing joint ventures in the United States and Europe, and the possibility of Fiat taking a large equity stake in Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However, talks dragged on and eventually broke off.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Ironically, Fiat would acquire a majority stake in Chrysler following its 2009 restructuring.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Iacocca received much credit for Chrysler's turnaround from near bankruptcy, with his commercials giving him celebrity status, and some mentioned him as a potential U.S. presidential candidate in 1988.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However the latter part of his tenure from 1988 onwards was less successful.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In addition, Iacocca enjoyed being in the spotlight and gradually isolated himself from his "Gang of Ford" managers that he had brought over from Ford Motor Company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] By 1992, the board pushed Iacocca to retire, albeit with a generous severance package.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Iacocca proposed Gerald Greenwald as his replacement, but that bought opposition from the board.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Iacocca stepped down as CEO and Chairman of Chrysler at the end of 1992, being succeeded in these posts by GM Europe president Robert Eaton.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Although Bob Lutz was the second-ranking executive in the company, he earlier opposed the merger with Fiat that Iacocca had championed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Due to their feud, Iacocca convinced the board to pass over Lutz for the chairmanship of Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However, Eaton and Lutz did develop a strong working relationship.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1978, Lee Iacocca, recently fired from being Ford's executive, was aggressively courted and brought in as CEO.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] At the time, Chrysler was losing millions, largely due to recalls of the company's Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volare, cars that Iacocca would later claim should have been delayed until prototypes were fully tested.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] He began rebuilding the entire company from the ground up, laying off many workers, selling the loss-making Chrysler Europe division to Peugeot for a nominal $1 (or $4.15 in 2021) and bringing in many former associates from his former company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Also from Ford, Iacocca brought to Chrysler the "Mini-Max" project, which would bear fruit in 1983 with the successful Dodge Caravan and Plymouth Voyager.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Henry Ford II had wanted nothing to do with the Mini-Max, a restyled version of the minivan that Toyota was selling in huge numbers in Asia and Latin America, which doomed the project at Ford.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Hal Sperlich, the driving force behind the Mini-Max at Ford had been fired a few months before Iacocca and was waiting for him at Chrysler, where the two would make automotive history.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Iacocca proved to be a capable public spokesman, appearing in advertisements to advise customers that "If you find a better car, buy it." He would also provide a rallying point for Japan-bashing and instilling pride in American products.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] His book *Talking Straight* was a response to Akio Morita's *Made in Japan*.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] As the 1990s dawned, Chrysler faced a renewed round of financial troubles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The US economy slipped into a recession following the 1987 Black Monday stock market crash and the Savings and Loan Crisis.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In addition, most of Chrysler's lineup was based on the proven but dated K-car platform, and critics routinely criticized their inability to produce fresh designs that were competitive with Japanese companies and Chrysler's Detroit rivals.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Engineering teams were now allowed to explore new designs, a process that was largely discouraged under Iacocca's tenure.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] François Castaing, by now Chrysler's vice president for Vehicle Engineering, had organized function teams, and incorporated the use of simultaneous engineering; This business process is now known as product lifecycle management.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] He also designed a new development approach in which teams of engineers focused on a single type of car platform, working on new models as a system from concept to production.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] An early adopter of PLM technology, Chrysler was able to become the auto industry's lowest-cost producer, recording development costs that were half of the industry average by the mid-1990s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1992, Chrysler introduced the LH platform, replacing the K-derived Chrysler New Yorker and Dodge Dynasty.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Like the LH platform's predecessor, the Eagle Premier, the LH cars featured longitudinally-mounted V6 engines with a front-wheel drive drivetrain, unusual in most U.S. front-wheel drive cars, but a hallmark of Renault's designs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The LH cars were the first to use Castaing's platform approach, and were produced in a record 39 months, compared to other Chrysler cars that took more than 50 months.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The LH cars competed directly against the Ford Taurus, mid-size cars from Japan, and GM's H and W platform cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] While Chrysler's sales never rose to the levels of those popular rivals, the LH vehicles succeeded in altering Chrysler's previously dowdy public image, recasting the automaker as an innovative design leader.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1995, Chrysler introduced the Neon small car to replace the Dodge Shadow and Plymouth Sundance, and the midsize JA platform vehicles replaced the Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] By 1996, the K platform and its derivatives had been phased out of production.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The continuing popularity of Jeep with the introduction of the 1992 Grand Cherokee and the 1997 Wrangler, bold new models such as the 1994 Dodge Ram pickup, Dodge Viper sports car, Plymouth Prowler hot rod, redesigned LH sedans and new minivans put the company in a strong position.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The success of Castaing's system was exemplified not just by the attraction of Daimler-Benz as the suitor for Chrysler, but by more than just a passing interest from General Motors and Toyota.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In the early 1990s, Chrysler set up car production in Austria, and began producing right hand drive Jeep models in a 1993 return to the UK market after a 15-year hiatus.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1991, Chrysler began the process of moving its corporate headquarters from its 1925 founding location of Highland Park, Michigan, to nearby Auburn Hills.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1995, former CEO Lee Iacocca assisted in billionaire Kirk Kerkorian's hostile takeover of Chrysler, which was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The next year, Kerkorian and Chrysler made a five-year agreement that includes a gag order preventing Iacocca from speaking publicly about Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 1998, Daimler-Benz and Chrysler had formed a 50–50 partnership.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler Corporation then was legally renamed DaimlerChrysler Motors Company LLC, while its total operations began doing business as Chrysler Group.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] This was initially declared to be a *merger of equals*, but it became evident that once Chrysler Chairman and CEO Bob Eaton retired, that Daimler would take majority control.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Other executives like President Thomas T.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Stallkamp, once considered the heir-apparent of Eaton, and Vice-Chairman Bob Lutz were soon forced out.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Eaton, Stallkamp, and Lutz had been described as the "triumvirate" responsible for Chrysler's successes in the late 1990s, with much credit going to Lutz's platform design teams.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Daimler-Benz got the remainder of Chrysler, excluding the Eagle brand, which was dissolved that year.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Then-Daimler-Benz CEO Juergen Schrempp had "promised a marriage made in heaven and huge synergies".
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Wiggers' concept of a platform strategy like the VW Group, was implemented only for a few models, so the synergy effects in development and production were too low.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However, it proved to be a disaster for Daimler, which poured billions of dollars into Chrysler, draining management and resources, and repeatedly dragging down its Mercedes-Benz luxury vehicle subsidiary.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Dieter Zetsche was appointed CEO of the Chrysler Group in 2000.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Plymouth brand was dissolved in 2001, and plans for cost cutting by sharing of platforms and components began.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] A return to rear-wheel drive was announced for a new line of full size cars, spearheaded by the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger and Dodge Magnum which used some Mercedes-Benz W211 components and offered a new HEMI V8 engine as a performance option.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] While the Magnum received a tepid reception in the market, the 300 and the Charger garnered much attention and sold well.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The partnership with Mitsubishi was dissolved as DaimlerChrysler divested its stake in the firm.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Financial performance improved and Chrysler was generating a significant part of Daimler-Chrysler's profits from 2004 to 2005, as the other subsidiary, Mercedes-Benz, incurred costs for restructuring.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] By 2005, Chrysler was said to be the healthiest of the Detroit Three automakers (compared to General Motors and Ford Motor Company).
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] As a result of Zetsche's apparent success in a turnaround of Chrysler, Juergen Schrempp, the CEO of parent company Daimler-Chrysler, was pressured to retire early.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Zetsche was elevated to CEO of Daimler-Chrysler on January 1, 2006, and Thomas W.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] LaSorda became president and CEO of Chrysler Group.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However, in 2006, while DCX's other subsidiary Mercedes-Benz turned a profit, Chrysler swung to a loss and analysts believed that the profitable years of 2004–05 would be unlikely to be return in the future.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] That led to suggestions that the eight-year merger would come to an end, as Mercedes (which made up around 33% of Daimler's $200 billion in 2006 revenues) did not get any competitive boost from Chrysler, and that Daimler would be a stronger and more profitable group without the U.S. unit.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Zetsche admitted that Chrysler offered no serious scale of advantages, though he initially insisted a spinoff was not being considered and said that management's first priority is to fix the problems at Chrysler by trimming production and redoubling efforts to boost its competitiveness.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Some suggest that Zetsche's tenure was a mixed success, with Chrysler still relying heavily on gas-guzzling SUVs and trucks, most of its product lineup was unsuccessful, despite using Mercedes-derived technologies.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Despite radical restructuring and improved models, analysts said that it was difficult to expect a solid recovery at Chrysler, due to the negative dynamics of the U.S. auto market and Chrysler's legacy labor and health care costs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In 2006, Zetsche had starred in the "Dr.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Z" ad campaign which cast him as an all-knowing, German-accented wizard of the auto industry, in TV spots and a website.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The strategy was to communicate that Chrysler was backed up by the same Teutonic know-how and discipline that has long made Mercedes-Benz one of the world's most prestigious brands.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However, the campaign was moth-balled in 2007.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Eight years since the merger, most customers did not know that Chrysler was owned by the same company that also produces Mercedes-Benz luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Some surveyed thought Zetsche was so smooth on screen—even to the point of head-butting a soccer ball perfectly in one take—that he was an actor and not the actual CEO.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] According to the April 2007 issue of Der Spiegel, CEO Dieter Zetsche expressed a desire to dismantle Chrysler and sell off the majority stake and at the same time keep Chrysler "dependent" upon Mercedes-Benz after the sale.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On April 4, 2007, Zetsche said that the company was negotiating the sale of Chrysler, which was rumored for weeks before the announcement.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The following day investor Kirk Kerkorian placed a 4.5 billion dollar bid for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On April 12, Magna International of Canada announced it was searching for partners to place a bid for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] DaimlerChrysler AG announced on May 14, 2007 that it would sell 80.1% of its stake in the Chrysler Group to Cerberus Capital Management for US$7.4 billion.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] DaimlerChrysler AG changed its name to Daimler AG.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler LLC unveiled a new company logo, a variation of the previously used Pentastar logo, and launched its new website on August 6, 2007.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Robert Nardelli became chairman and CEO.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In the resulting management shuffle, LaSorda was relegated to the number two position as President and Vice Chairman of Chrysler LLC, Jim Press, previously President of Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A., Inc., was appointed Co-President and Vice Chairman.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] While LaSorda's titles at Chrysler LLC officially stated that he was in charge of manufacturing, procurement and supply, employee relations, global business development and alliances, his actual role in the company was largely to find a new partner or buyer for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Cerberus Capital was said to be less interested in rebuilding the auto manufacturer as a long-term investment, rather it was focused on turning a short-term profit though a leveraged buyout.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The new company experienced its first labor dispute on October 10, 2007.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] A strike deadline of 11 am had been set by the United Auto Workers (UAW) union leadership pending successful negotiation of a new contract patterned after the pact with GM.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] As the talks progressed past the deadline, most Chrysler unionized workers walked off their jobs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] With media speculation about the impact of a long strike, an impromptu announcement after 5 pm the same day indicated that a tentative agreement had been reached, thus ending the walkout after just over six hours.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler collaborated with Tata Motors Limited of India: Tata's all-electric Ace mini truck will be sold through Chrysler's GEM, Global Electric Motorcars division.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler announced in February 2008 that it would be reducing its product line from 30 models to 15 models.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler was reported in August 2008 to be in talks with Fiat.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In October 2008, Cerberus and General Motors discussed an exchange of GM's 49% stake in GMAC for Chrysler, potentially merging two of Detroit's "Big Three" automakers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] These talks did not come to fruition, and were discontinued the next month.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On October 24, 2008, Chrysler announced a 25% cut (5,000 jobs) in its salaried and contract workforce in November 2008.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Jennifer Granholm announced that she, along with 5 other governors, sent a letter to Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson and Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke requesting emergency funding for the Detroit Big Three Automakers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On the same day, General Motors asked the Treasury Department of the United States for $10 billion to help restructure both their company and possible future sibling, Chrysler so that in turn, they can become one massive company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On October 23, 2008, Daimler announced that its stake in Chrysler had a book value of zero dollars after write offs and charges.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On November 5, 2008 it was published that Chrysler sales in the US market have fallen 34.9 percent in only 12 months.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] A week later, Chrysler CEO Robert Nardelli said, in a speech at an Ernst & Young conference, that the company can only remain viable by forming an alliance with another automaker, domestic or global, as well as receiving government assistance in the form of an equity stake.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Several days later, Chrysler together with Ford and General Motors, sought financial aid at a Congressional hearing in Washington D.C. in the face of worsening conditions caused by the automotive industry crisis.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] All three companies were unsuccessful and were invited to draft a new action plan for the sustainability of the industry.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] At the beginning of December 2008, amid the 2008 automobile crisis, Chrysler announced that they were dangerously low on cash and may not survive past 2009.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] After the defeat of the auto bailout in the Senate, Chrysler stated that they would most likely file for bankruptcy and shut down all operations permanently.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On December 17, 2008, Chrysler announced that it planned to halt production at all 30 of its manufacturing plants through January 19, 2009.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In addition, Chrysler Financial announced that it would charge fees on dealers holding inventories of new cars and trucks that are unsold after more than 360 days, and will require immediate payment of all remaining balances on inventories of used vehicles that remain unsold after six months.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Bush announced a $13.4 billion rescue loan for the American automakers, including Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler's 2008 performance was hard hit among the Big Three U.S. automakers, with 398,119 automobiles and 1,055,003 trucks sold during the year.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On March 13, 2009, LaSorda told the House of Commons of Canada finance committee that the initial GM-CAW deal was insufficient and that Chrysler would demand an hourly wage cut of $20, breaking the Canadian Auto Workers's negotiating pattern set by GM.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] He suggested that Chrysler may withdraw from Canada if it fails to achieve more substantial cost savings from the CAW.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Meanwhile Chrysler LLC has since filed for bankruptcy, though Fiat would continue to implement the strategic alliance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On March 7, 2009, Chrysler Vice-Chairman Jim Press stated that current sales volume is sufficient to keep the company going as sales should rise in the coming months.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Chrysler executive also noted the automaker's February retail sales were better than Ford's as Chrysler continued to curtail lower-margin fleet sales.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] He also said the volumes being forecast for 2009 were within the estimates Chrysler envisioned in preparing its viability plan for the federal government.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On March 30, 2009, the White House announced it would provide an additional $6 billion in further support to Chrysler contingent on the company finalizing an alliance with Fiat before the end of April.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Talks and hearings at U.S.Treasury in Washington, D.C. went on throughout the following month.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On March 30, 2009 President Barack Obama issued a US Government guarantee of Chrysler's warranty liabilities, and publicly stated the U.S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Government will back the warranties on Chrysler vehicles if the company were to go out of business.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On January 20, 2009, Fiat S.p.A. and Chrysler LLC announced that they have a non-binding term sheet to form a global alliance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] By mid-April, as talks intensified between the two automakers to reach an agreement by a government-imposed deadline of April 30, Fiat's initial stake was reported to be 20% with some influence on the structure of top management of the company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] However, Fiat has warned that the merger would not take place if Chrysler fails to reach an agreement with the UAW and the Canadian Auto Workers' Union.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On April 26, 2009, it appeared as if Chrysler had reached a deal with the unions which would meet federal requirements, though details were not made available.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler said the union agreement "provides the framework needed to ensure manufacturing competitiveness and helps to meet the guidelines set forth by the U.S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Treasury Department." Chrysler filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection at the Federal Bankruptcy Court of the Southern District of New York, in Manhattan, on April 30, 2009, and announced an alliance with Fiat.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Both the White House and Chrysler expressed hope for a "surgical" bankruptcy lasting 30 to 60 days, with the result of reducing the company's liabilities and post-bankruptcy emergence in stronger financial shape.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The submitted court documents indicated that there would be a reorganization plan presented to the court in 120 days, on August 28, 2009.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Prior to the bankruptcy filing, Chrysler had received $US 4.5 billion in financing from the U.S. government, under a George W.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Bush administration plan, in December 2008, after Congress declined to approve legislation to provide federal loans.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On May 1, 2009, Chrysler LLC filed for bankruptcy, and LaSorda stepped down as President and Vice-Chairman and retired, despite Fiat urging him to stay on.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On May 14, 2009 Chrysler filed with the bankruptcy court to terminate the dealership agreements of 789, or about 25% of its dealerships.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On June 1, 2009 a US bankruptcy court approved a plan which spells out that the new Chrysler company called "Chrysler Group LLC".
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The VEBA formed by the United Auto Workers Union to provide health care for Chrysler retirees will hold 55%.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Minority stakes will be held by Fiat (20%) and the US (8%) and Canadian (2%) governments.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Fiat has stated it plans to increase its share to 35% if Chrysler meets certain goals.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On June 9, 2009, the Supreme Court published its denial of the applications for a stay of the sale from the three Indiana funds, allowing the sale of assets to "New Chrysler" to proceed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] According to the two page decision and order, the Indiana funds "have not carried the burden" of demonstrating that the Supreme Court needed to intervene.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Department of the Treasury issued a statement saying: "We are gratified that not a single court that reviewed this matter, including the U.S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Supreme, found any fault whatsoever with the handling of this matter by either Chrysler or the U.S. government." The proposed sale of assets is scheduled to close on Wednesday, June 10, 2009, when the money to finance the deal is wired by the government.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Fiat will receive equity in the New Chrysler through its contribution of automobile platforms as a base for a new line of Chrysler cars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On June 10, 2009, 41 days after filing for bankruptcy protection, the sale of most of Chrysler assets to "New Chrysler", formally known as Chrysler Group LLC, was completed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The federal government financed the deal with US$6.6 billion in financing, paid to the "Old Chrysler", formally called Old Carco LLC.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The transfer does not include eight manufacturing locations, nor many parcels of real estate, nor equipment leases.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Contracts with 789 U.S. auto dealerships, who are being dropped, were not transferred.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Fiat initially owned a minority 20% stake of Chrysler Group LLC with the option of taking additional equity up to a 35% stake if certain operational and capitalization goals were achieved.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The United Auto Workers’ union retiree health care trust fund (Volunteer Employee Benefit Association) was the majority owner, with 55 percent when Fiat reached its target holding of 35%.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The U.S. and Canadian governments initially held minority stakes of 8% and 2%, respectively, of the new Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On May 24, 2011, Fiat paid back $7.6 billion in U.S. and Canadian government loans.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On July 21, Fiat bought the Chrysler shares held by the United States Treasury.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] With the purchase, Chrysler once again became foreign owned; this time Italian car maker Fiat gained majority ownership and control of Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The United States government's involvement in the Chrysler bankruptcy cost the U.S. taxpayer $1.3 billion.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In early 2009, Chrysler Group, based in Auburn Hills, Michigan, became majority owned by the United Auto Workers Voluntary Employee Beneficiary Association trust.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In June 2009 Fiat gained ownership of Chrysler Group as a part of Chrysler's restructuring plan, and eventually gained 58% total stake in the company.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Fiat stated plans for the Chrysler brand and Lancia to codevelop products, with some vehicles being shared.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Olivier Francois, Lancia's CEO, took over as CEO of the Chrysler division in October 2009.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Fiat has stated that, depending on the market, some Chrysler cars will be sold as Lancias and vice versa.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Francois planned to reestablish the Chrysler brand as an upscale brand, a position somewhat muddied since the K-car era in the 80's, and especially after the Plymouth brand was discontinued.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] At the 2010 Detroit Auto Show, A Chrysler badged Lancia Delta was on display, likely the first Lancia to be sold as a Chrysler and possibly as a replacement for the Chrysler PT Cruiser.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Dodge, Jeep, Chrysler get makeover by refreshing, redesigning or replacing every car and truck, swapping out engines and creating vehicles people want.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On 16 December 2014, Chrysler Group LLC announced a name change to FCA US LLC.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] With its inception in 1925, Chrysler's logo was a round medallion with a ribbon bearing the name 'CHRYSLER' in uppercase block letters.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] It The logo resembled a seal that was used at government fairs as an award.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The original symbol fell out of use in 1954 and was forgotten for several decades until the company decided to return to its origins.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The logo was designed by one of Chrysler engineers, Oliver Clark, by request of company's founder Walter Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The seal was dropped in 1955 and would return in 1993, being placed at the center of a winged emblem in 1997.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Virgil Exner's radical "Forward Look" redesign of Chrysler Corporation's vehicles for the 1955 model year was underscored by the company's adoption of a logo by the same name.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Forward Look logo consisted of two overlapped boomerang shapes, suggesting space age rocket-propelled motion.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] As the Forward Look styling cycle was ending, Chrysler President Lynn Townsend sought a new logo usable by all of Chrysler's worldwide divisions and subsidiaries, automotive and non-automotive, on packaging, stationery, signage and advertising.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] He wanted something that would be immediately identifiable as Chrysler's mark to anyone who saw it, in any culture.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] In September 1962, the company adopted a logo named "Pentastar", made of five triangles arranged so their bases formed the sides of a pentagon.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The gaps in between the triangles formed a star in the middle of the pentagon.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Pentastar was simple and easily recognizable, even on revolving signs, and was not tied to any particular automotive styling feature as had been the previous Forward Look logo.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Because the symbol contained no text, it facilitated Chrysler's expansion in international markets.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Pentastar was extensively used on dealer signage, advertisements, and promotional brochures, as well as on Chrysler products themselves.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler-Plymouth literature, advertisements, and dealership signage used a blue Pentastar or a white one on a blue background, while Dodge used a red Pentastar or a white one on a red background.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Divisional logos such as Dodge's Fratzog were gradually phased out until, by 1981, all Chrysler divisions used only the Pentastar.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Pentastar logo was placed on the lower passenger-side fender of all Chrysler products, including non-US brands, from 1963 into the 1972 model year.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] It was placed on the passenger-side fender so it could be viewed by passers-by, a subtle method of getting the symbol ingrained in the public's mind: a nameplate has to be read, but a symbol is quickly recognizable without reading.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Thus left-hand drive cars had the Pentastar on the right fender, while right-hand drive cars had it on the left.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Starting in the 1980s, hood ornaments on Chrysler-brand vehicles used a gem-like version of the Pentastar to signify the brand's upscale status.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Pentastar's final badging appearance was on rare versions of the 1996 Plymouth Voyager.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] It was also applied to the steering wheel, keys, and fenders of the Voyager and the other Chrysler NS minivans into 2000.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Pentastar continued to represent Chrysler until the merger with Daimler in 1998, when it was retired.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Among the few remaining traces of this motif was a large, star-shaped window at DaimlerChrysler's American headquarters in Auburn Hills, Michigan, and Pentastar Aviation, a former DaimlerChrysler subsidiary which reverted to its original name after being purchased by a member of the Ford family.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Many dealerships still have signage and other traces still visually apparent to the Pentastar, where a five-Pentastar logo remains in use as the logo of the "Five Star Dealer" service rank.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Despite having been officially retired under Daimler, the Pentastar continued to be used as the identifying trademark or logo on Chrysler Group parts, as seen on window glass, on individual components, molded plastic assemblies, and larger parts such as (reportedly) engine blocks.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Pentastar was officially reintroduced in 2007; however, was replaced with the stylized letters "FCA" for Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Even though Chrysler became a part of Stellantis in 2021, which was formed by the merger of FCA and the French automaker PSA Group, the Pentastar logo is still maintained at the headquarters' building.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Incidentally, the Pentastar is also used as the badge of the United States Army's V Corps, and a similar symbol was used as the semi-official emblem of the League of Nations in 1939.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Divisional logos began to supplant the company-wide Pentastar application in the early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Dodge division phased in a ram's-head logo beginning with the 1993 Intrepid and Spirit.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The Chrysler brand began using a medallion based on its original logo starting with the 1995 Cirrus, Concorde, and Sebring.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] This logo was applied to all Chryslers by 1996.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] That same year, Plymouth adopted a new sailboat logo, which was a simplified version of the brand's pre-Pentastar Mayflower ship logo.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The design shown here is an adaptation of the original medallion logo which Chrysler used on its cars at its inception in 1925.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The logo was revived for the Chrysler division in 1997, and is often surrounded by a pair of silver wings.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] When sold to Cerberus, Chrysler readopted the Pentastar (see above) as their corporate logo, although the winged logo is still used on the cars themselves.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] On May 17, 2007, an internal email stated that Chrysler was going to revive the Pentastar logo, in updated form, after their split from Daimler.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The new three-dimensional Pentastar was formally introduced when Chrysler LLC began doing business as a private company in August 2007.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] Chrysler cars retained a modified version of the winged logo.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] With the formation of Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, the stylized letters "FCA" replaced the Pentastar as the official logo.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] The move angered several Chrysler fans who spawned a Facebook page and a petition drive to save it.
[src:chrysler-imperial/airtemp-p02] When FCA and the PSA Group merged in 2021 to form Stellantis, Chrysler LLC Group (named "Stellantis North America", officially "FCA US"), adopted the Stellantis brand used worldwide.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-imperial/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The **Chrysler Imperial**, introduced in 1926, was Chrysler's top-of-the-line vehicle for much of its history.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Models were produced under the Chrysler name until 1954, after which Imperial became a standalone make; and again from 1990–93.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The company positioned the cars as a prestige marque to rival Cadillac, Continental, Lincoln, Duesenberg, Pierce Arrow, Cord, and Packard.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] According to *Antique Automobile*, "The adjective 'imperial' according to Webster's Dictionary means sovereign, supreme, superior or of unusual size or excellence.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] For several decades and multiple generations, the Imperial was the exclusive Chrysler and the favorite choice of luxurious transportation for senior executive leadership, government officials, royalty and various celebrities in comparison to the more affordable Chrysler New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Over the years the appearance, technological advancements and luxurious accommodations updated with the latest trends and fashionable appearances.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Limousines, town cars and convertibles were the usual appearances, while special coachwork choices were provided by the industry's best providers, to include Derham, Fleetwood, LeBaron, and others.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Chrysler Imperial rose was cultivated in 1952 and used to promote the brand.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Chrysler decided to compete with North American marques Cadillac, Lincoln, Packard, Pierce Arrow, Studebaker, Cord, and Duesenberg in the luxury car field, while the newly formed company only had a large displacement straight-six to offer.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The new model, called Imperial, had a new engine that was slightly larger than the company's standard straight 6 installed in the Chrysler Six.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] It was a 288.6 cu in (4.7 L) six-cylinder with seven bearing blocks and pressure lubrication of 92 brake horsepower (69 kW).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Large displacement engines provided the horsepower and torque clients wanted and due to the low quality of gasoline fuel at the time, and low compression ratios, 50 bhp was more than adequate.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] It is estimated that the rating equivalent of early gasoline available varied from 40 to 60 octane and that the "High-Test", sometimes referred to as "fighting grade", probably averaged 50 to 65 octane.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The front axle was solid and the suspension consisted of semi-elliptic leaf springs while the rear suspension was a differential axle, and also using semi-elliptic leaf springs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The use of the "imperial" name being exclusively used on Chrysler's flagship had been previously used by Buick, Cadillac and Packard for top level limousines.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The hood ornament/radiator cap was a stylized Viking Winged helmet.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The car set a transcontinental speed record in the year it was introduced, driving more than 6,500 miles (10,460 km) in the week.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The car was chosen as the pace car for the 1926 Indianapolis 500.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The model was designated E-80, the 80 being after the "guaranteed" 80 miles per hour (129 km/h) all-day cruising speed.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Acceleration was also brisk, breaking 20 seconds to 60 miles per hour (97 km/h).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Four-speed manual transmission was added in 1930.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The attention to luxury and multiple bodystyles was a similar approach to one Mr.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Chrysler used as president of the Buick Motor Company, his employer from 1911 to 1919.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Chrysler offered a variety of body styles: a two/four-passenger roadster (four passenger if car had the rumble seat), a four-seat coupé, five-passenger sedan and phaeton, and a seven-passenger top-of-the-line limousine.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The limo had a glass partition between the front and rear passenger compartments.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Imperials could be distinguished from Chrysler products by the use of a distinctive scalloped hood and radiator shell and a 120 in (3,048 mm) wheelbase, which shared an appearance with Packard and the Buick Master Six.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Berline Limousine was listed at US$3,595 ($65,379 in 2025 dollars ).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The 1927 Imperial Series 80 saw minor engineering improvements, while the high compression "Red Head" 288.6 cu in (4.7 L) straight-six was the only engine available on a choice of 120 in (3,048 mm), 127 in (3,226 mm) or special order 133 in (3,378 mm) wheelbases.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Five two-door coachwork choices included roadsters and convertible, while there were nine sedan, town car, phaeton and limousine choices.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Standard equipment on roadster and phaeton open-body coachwork selections included wind wings and leather exterior door trim panels, while many cars were painted in contrasting two-tone paint.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The convertible was equipped with functioning landau irons.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] In 1927, an Imperial was driven at a high speed along the Lincoln Highway from San Francisco to New York to Los Angeles, covering a total distance of 6,726 mi (10,824.4 km) non-stop, with an average speed of 40 mph (64 km/h).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] 1928 offered a 136 in (3,454 mm) wheelbase with the designation Series 80L.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Coachwork choices expanded with five provided by Briggs, and six choices from LeBaron, one Derham Convertible Sedan, one Phaeton from Locke, and four Dietrich convertible coupes and sedans, listing the Dietrich Convertible Sedan at US$6,795 ($127,406 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Coachbuilder Locke provided four convertible choices in both coupe and sedan configurations, and hydraulic four wheel brakes were now standard on all Chrysler products.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The all-new 1931 "Chrysler Imperial 8" introduced the new in-line 8-cylinder engine which was shared with the Chrysler Eight Series CP in smaller displacements.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The car received a new 384.4 cu in (6.3 L) Chrysler flathead Straight-8 with a Stromberg Model DD-3 carburetor.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Imperial introduced a vee-type radiator, a long straight hood that displayed "torpedo" styling, and wide flowing fenders with a split and slanted windshield and showed visual similarities to the Cord L-29.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Various features considered luxurious in nature at the time included dual sun visors, adjustable front seats and steering column, rust-proof fenders, wire-spoked wheels, automatic heater control, safety glass and Lockheed supplied hydraulic brakes.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] To minimize engine vibration from being felt by passengers, an isolation feature called "Floating Power" was introduced.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Imperial Series CG offered four sedan coachwork choices from Briggs, while LeBaron offered four convertible coupe and sedan choices.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] At least ten Individual Custom 2-door coupes were documented from individual coachwork providers Waterhouse, Drauz and LeBaron.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] These were custom built to specification, and were variously equipped with anything the customer desired—even a Dictaphone.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Prices ranged from US$2,745 ($58,114 in 2025 dollars) for the factory supplied four-door, five-passenger Sedan to US$3,575 ($75,685 in 2025 dollars) for the LeBaron Dual Cowl Phaeton.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Stock car driver Harry Hartz set numerous speed records with a 1933 Imperial sedan at Daytona Beach, Florida.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] A roadster was entered in the 1931 24 Hours of Le Mans competition but did not finish due to radiator failure.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] It was introduced shortly after the Rolls-Royce Phantom II, Mercedes-Benz 770, Packard Eight, Duesenberg Model J, Renault Reinastella, Cadillac Series 355, and Lincoln K-series.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Total documented CG production shows that 3,228 of all body style choices were manufactured, including chassis only supplied to individual coachwork providers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] A stylized gazelle statuette was added to the Viking Winged helmet radiator cap and hood ornament for all Imperial vehicles starting in 1931.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Model year 1932 introduced the junior Series CH Imperial while the previous Series CG became the Series CL and took the name Imperial Custom to continue to provide individually requested, customized vehicles.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Series CH was related to the Chrysler Series CP in that the straight-eight engine, and most features were shared while the Imperial Series CH was offered with many standard features that were optional on the Series CP.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Series CH and CL featured all steel body work, a double drop "girder truss" chassis frame, split windshields, dual sun visors, and trumpet horns.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The ignition was provided by Delco-Remy, the brakes were hydraulic and the transmission was a four-speed manual transmission with an optional automatic vacuum operated clutch.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The body styles offered on the Series CH were a two-door, two-passenger roadster convertible with available rumble seat, a four-door sedan or a four-door convertible.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The roadster listed price was US$1,925 ($45,425 in 2025 dollars) while the four-door convertible was US$2,195 ($51,797 in 2025 dollars) which made the more esteemed "Imperial" brand almost identically priced to "Chrysler" branded products, while the engine displacement on the Series CH was larger.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Records show that 32 Series CL Sedan Limousine by LeBaron were sold for US$3,295 ($77,754 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Series CQ Imperial was all-new for 1933 from the previous Series CH and the wheelbase lost 10 in (254 mm) and the 298.65 cu in (4.9 L) Chrysler I8 had reduced displacement.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Three two-door, two-passenger coupes to include a Victoria and Roadster Convertible, and two four-door, five-passenger choices with one sedan convertible were offered by Briggs.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Mechanical improvements offered were a silent, helical gear three-speed transmission, an improved oil filter and an automatic choke for the Stromberg IV Model EX-32 carburetor.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Only three sedan coachwork choices were offered for the Series CL sedan with the 146 in (3,708 mm) wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Production records document 3,838 Series CQ and 151 Series CL were manufactured, including six Chassis and Cowl only requests.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Chrysler Imperial introduced in 1934 offered the 'Airflow' design, reflecting an interest in streamlining.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] It was the first car to be designed in a wind tunnel.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Initial tests indicated that the standard car of the 1920s worked best in the wind-tunnel when pointed backwards with the curved rear deck facing forward.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] It led to a rethinking of the fundamental design of Chrysler's cars with a primary focus on reducing wind noise inside the passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Both engine and passenger compartment were moved forward, giving better balance and ride.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] An early form of unibody construction was employed, giving them a durability advantage in comparison to body on frame construction.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] It continued to offer a Chrysler engine vibration isolation feature called "Floating Power" and was one of the first automobiles to offer a one piece curved windshield.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Chrysler offered both the conventional Airstream models along with the Airflow models under the "Chrysler" marque but only offered the "Imperial" marque with Airflow models.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The longer wheelbase Imperial Custom Airflow Series CX offered only sedan choices, to include Town Sedan and Limousine choices on a 137.5 in (3,492 mm) wheelbase for US$2,345 ($56,437 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The top level Imperial Custom Airflow Series CW offered a four-door Sedan, Limousine or Town Limousine for US$5,000 ($120,336 in 2025 dollars) using a 146.5 in (3,721 mm) wheelbase and the 384.8 cu in (6.3 L) Straight Eight.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Documented production numbers for 1934 show 2,277 Series CV, 106 Series CX and 67 Series CW were produced.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The public was put off by the unconventional styling and the "Airstream" appearance on Chryslers outsold the "Airflow" by 3 to 1.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Total production documented records show 2,598 Series C-2 coupes and sedans were manufactured, while just 125 Series C-3 rolled off the assembly line, accounting for both coupe and sedan production.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The top level Series CW recorded only 32 limousines that could accommodate eight passengers, offering four different coachwork choices for a minimum listed price of US$5,000 ($117,415 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] 1936 was the last year for the "Airflow" appearance, while there were some enhancements and features added to entice buyers.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] A new grille, all-steel roof construction and a luggage compartment was added.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The wheelbase was lengthened and the doors and side windows.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The front windshield was either split or curved one piece on the Imperial Custom and continued to be extendable from the base outwards while a separate retractable cowl ventilator remained to provide fresh air inside the passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Production numbers continued to fall to a total of 4,500 Series C-10 sedans and coupes and 75 Series C-11 sedans and limousines.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] A total of 10 Series CW were documented to be sold while the actual manufacture date were previous years that were registered, and dated as 1936 models.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The pricing structure was simplified as US$1,475 ($34,637 in 2025 dollars ) for the Series C-10 for the coupe or sedan, and US$2,475 ($58,120 in 2025 dollars) for the Series C-11 sedan or limousine.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] While 1936 was the most profitable season for Chrysler since 1929, the Airflow program was cancelled, and the Imperial Custom Airflows are recognized as Classics by the Classic Car Club of America.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Chrysler reverted to body on frame construction and there were three models in this generation designated as Imperial.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The polarizing appearance was modified with a return to "torpedo" styling, sharing the appearance of a long, straight hood and cowl and moving the headlights outwards into the front fenders with the more successful "Airstream" appearance.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Series C-14 offered the straight eight, shared with the Chrysler Royal C-16 .
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The Series C-15 was the Imperial Custom and the Town Sedan Limousine, with blind rear quarter panels and was available on request.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The top level Imperial Custom Series CW continued to be offered but was very exclusive, using a 146.5 in (3,721 mm) wheelbase while eliminating the "Airflow" nameplate.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Innovations for 1937 included built-in defroster vents, safety-type interior hardware (such as flexible door handles and recessed controls on the dash), seat-back padding, and fully insulated engine mounts.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Brakes were 13-inch drums, then in 1939 they expanded to 14 inches, but shrunk to 12-inch drums in 1940.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Unusually for ventilation, it had a concealed crank to extend the base of the split windshield outward and the top edge of the engine hood was hinged at the cowl and opened from the grille and up.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Access to the engine was accommodated with side hood panels that were released by catches on the inside.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] An Imperial Custom Series C-15 Convertible Sedan by Derham was used as the AAA Official Car at the 1937 Indy 500 and was painted silver and black to celebrate the racetracks 25th anniversary.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] According to 1937 documented records, 11,976 Series C-14 Touring Sedans were produced at a listed price of US$1,100 ($24,635 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] While the Imperial Custom Series CW was offered in its final year for 1937, documentation does not record that one was built, while three 1937 Series CW were recorded to have been updated with 1936 appearance features and LeBaron bodywork.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The first one was built for the Hershey family who had an antique car collection at the time now called the AACA Museum in Hershey, Pennsylvania.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The second Series CW was built for The President of the Philippines Manuel L.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Quezon, the first president of the Spanish Commonwealth of the Philippines and is maintained by the government.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] The third car was built for radio personality Major Edward Bowes which later joined a car collection of Frank Kleptz of Terre Haute, Indiana.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] A *Life* magazine article written in 1940 quoted the value of Major Bowes car at US$25,000 ($574,525 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] According to records, after the death of Mr.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] Bowes the car returned to Chrysler in 1941.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] It was allegedly repainted black from the original Brewster Green and put into wartime service in 1942, used by Admiral Chester Nimitz as a staff car.
[src:chrysler-imperial/chrysler-imperial] For 1938, The Series C-19 was shared with the Imperial and all-new New York Special which became the New Yorker in 1939.
